// Unit 32: Kultur und Identität
// Level: B2

const UNIT_32 =
{n:32,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Kultur und Identität",sub:"Wer bin ich?",icon:"🎭",level:"B2.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
{id:"deu_r32l1",title:"Im Museum",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Im Museum",desc:"Neues Museum Berlin. Yilmaz and Verumius walk through the galleries together. Art provokes questions about identity, origin, and belonging.",goals:["Learn core vocabulary for identity and culture","Discuss what belonging means","Begin thinking about diversity and tolerance"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Identit\u00e4t",src:"identity",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'identitas' (sameness). 'Wer bin ich?' is the\nfundamental Identit\u00e4tsfrage in German discourse.",example:"A: Was bedeutet Identit\u00e4t f\u00fcr dich?\nB: Identit\u00e4t ist, wer ich wirklich bin.\nA: Kann sich die Identit\u00e4t ver\u00e4ndern?\nB: Ja, sie entwickelt sich ein Leben lang.",exampleSrc:"A: What does identity mean to you?\nB: Identity is who I really am.\nA: Can identity change?\nB: Yes, it develops throughout a lifetime.",funFact:"The Latin root 'identitas' meant sameness, but in German, Identit\u00e4t spans personal, cultural, and national dimensions. The Fugen-s enables rich compounds: Identit\u00e4tskrise, Identit\u00e4tspolitik."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Bewusstsein",src:"consciousness, awareness",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Bewusst' (aware) + 'sein' (being). Literally: the state\nof being aware. Philosophers love this word.",example:"A: Was ist kulturelles Bewusstsein?\nB: Die F\u00e4higkeit, andere Kulturen zu verstehen.\nA: Wie entwickelt man Bewusstsein?\nB: Durch Reisen, Lesen und Zuh\u00f6ren.",exampleSrc:"A: What is cultural awareness?\nB: The ability to understand other cultures.\nA: How does one develop awareness?\nB: Through traveling, reading, and listening.",funFact:"'Bewusst' (aware) + 'sein' (being). Literally: the state of being aware. Philosophers from Hegel to Habermas have written volumes about Bewusstsein. 'Kulturelles Bewusstsein' (cultural awareness) is a modern educational goal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Herkunft",src:"origin, heritage",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Her' (from/hither) + 'Kunft' (coming). Where you come\nfrom. 'Herkunftsland' appears on every German form.",example:"A: Woher ist deine Herkunft?\nB: Meine Familie kommt aus der T\u00fcrkei.\nA: Die Herkunft pr\u00e4gt uns alle.\nB: Ja, aber sie definiert uns nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is your heritage from?\nB: My family comes from Turkey.\nA: Heritage shapes us all.\nB: Yes, but it does not define us.",funFact:"'Her' (from/hither) + 'Kunft' (coming). 'Herkunftsland' (country of origin) appears on every German form. Your Herkunft shapes but need not define you."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Tradition",src:"tradition",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'traditio' (handing over). Same word internationally.\nGermans distinguish Brauch (living custom) from Tradition.",example:"A: Welche Traditionen pflegt ihr?\nB: Weihnachten und Zuckerfest.\nA: Zwei Traditionen in einer Familie?\nB: Ja, das ist normal bei uns.",exampleSrc:"A: Which traditions do you maintain?\nB: Christmas and Sugar Feast.\nA: Two traditions in one family?\nB: Yes, that is normal for us.",funFact:"Germans distinguish between living traditions (Br\u00e4uche) and inherited customs (\u00dcberlieferungen). The Latin root 'traditio' literally meant handing something over, generation to generation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vielfalt",src:"diversity, variety",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Viel' (many) + 'Falt' (fold). Literally: many-foldedness.\n'Kulturelle Vielfalt' is celebrated in modern German politics.",example:"A: Was macht Berlin besonders?\nB: Die kulturelle Vielfalt.\nA: Vielfalt bedeutet Reichtum?\nB: Ja, Vielfalt bereichert alle.",exampleSrc:"A: What makes Berlin special?\nB: The cultural diversity.\nA: Diversity means richness?\nB: Yes, diversity enriches everyone.",funFact:"'Viel' (many) + 'Falt' (fold). Literally: many-foldedness. 'Kulturelle Vielfalt' (cultural diversity) is celebrated in modern German political discourse. The word implies richness in difference."},
{type:"mc",q:"Woher kommt das Wort 'Herkunft'?",opts:["her (von) + Kunft (Kommen)","Herr + Kunft","Herz + Kunst","Heer + Zukunft"],ans:"her (von) + Kunft (Kommen)",hint:"A compound of two morphemes: one meaning 'from/hither', the other meaning 'coming'. Describes origin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Toleranz",src:"tolerance",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'tolerantia' (endurance). Lessing's play 'Nathan\nder Weise' (1779) made Toleranz a central German value.",example:"A: Was bedeutet Toleranz?\nB: Andere so akzeptieren, wie sie sind.\nA: Ist Toleranz immer einfach?\nB: Nein, aber sie ist notwendig.",exampleSrc:"A: What does tolerance mean?\nB: Accepting others as they are.\nA: Is tolerance always easy?\nB: No, but it is necessary.",funFact:"Lessing's play 'Nathan der Weise' (1779) made Toleranz a cornerstone of German values. Its Ring Parable argues all religions deserve equal respect. The Latin root 'tolerantia' originally meant endurance."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Vorurteil",src:"prejudice",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Vor' (before) + 'Urteil' (judgment). A judgment made\nbefore knowing the facts. The word reveals the problem.",example:"A: Hast du Vorurteile?\nB: Jeder hat welche, leider.\nA: Kann man Vorurteile abbauen?\nB: Ja, durch Begegnung und Dialog.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have prejudices?\nB: Everyone does, unfortunately.\nA: Can one reduce prejudices?\nB: Yes, through encounter and dialogue.",funFact:"'Vor' (before) + 'Urteil' (judgment). A judgment made before knowing the facts. 'Vorurteile abbauen' (to reduce prejudices). The word itself reveals the problem: judging before examining."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wahrnehmung",src:"perception",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Wahr' (true) + 'Nehmung' (taking). Literally: taking in\ntruth. How you perceive the world around you.",example:"A: Die Wahrnehmung ist subjektiv.\nB: Ja, jeder sieht die Welt anders.\nA: Kann man die Wahrnehmung trainieren?\nB: Ja, durch bewusstes Beobachten.",exampleSrc:"A: Perception is subjective.\nB: Yes, everyone sees the world differently.\nA: Can one train perception?\nB: Yes, through conscious observation.",funFact:"'Wahr' (true) + 'Nehmung' (taking). Literally: taking in truth. 'Die Wahrnehmung ver\u00e4ndert sich' (perception changes). A philosophical powerhouse of a word."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ein {1} ist ein Urteil, das man fällt, bevor man die Fakten kennt.",a:["Vorurteil"],opts:["Bewusstsein","Vorurteil","Zusammenleben","Toleranz"],hint:"Vor (before) + Urteil (judgment). The word itself reveals the problem: judging before examining.",sSrc:"A prejudice is a judgment one makes before knowing the facts."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l1b",title:"Im Museum (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Im Museum (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit",src:"belonging, affiliation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Zu' (to) + 'geh\u00f6ren' (to belong) + '-igkeit.' The feeling\nof being part of something. What every immigrant seeks.",example:"A: F\u00fchlst du Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit zu Berlin?\nB: Ja, inzwischen schon.\nA: Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit braucht Zeit.\nB: Und Offenheit von beiden Seiten.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel a sense of belonging to Berlin?\nB: Yes, by now I do.\nA: Belonging takes time.\nB: And openness from both sides.",funFact:"'Zu' (to) + 'geh\u00f6ren' (to belong) + '-igkeit.' The feeling of being part of something. 'Ein Gef\u00fchl der Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit' (a sense of belonging). What every immigrant seeks."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Zusammenleben",src:"coexistence, living together",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Zusammen' (together) + 'Leben' (life/living). 'Friedliches\nZusammenleben' is peaceful coexistence. An ongoing project.",example:"A: Wie funktioniert das Zusammenleben?\nB: Durch Respekt und Kommunikation.\nA: Friedliches Zusammenleben ist das Ziel?\nB: Ja, f\u00fcr alle in der Gesellschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: How does coexistence work?\nB: Through respect and communication.\nA: Peaceful coexistence is the goal?\nB: Yes, for everyone in society.",funFact:"'Zusammen' (together) + 'Leben' (life/living). 'Friedliches Zusammenleben' (peaceful coexistence). Germany's multicultural Zusammenleben is an ongoing project that shapes daily life."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gesellschaftlich",src:"social, societal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Gesellschaft' (society) + '-lich.' More formal than 'sozial.'\nGesellschaftlich addresses the structure of society.",example:"A: Was sind gesellschaftliche Ver\u00e4nderungen?\nB: Ver\u00e4nderungen in der ganzen Gesellschaft.\nA: Gesellschaftlich oder sozial?\nB: Gesellschaftlich ist formeller und breiter.",exampleSrc:"A: What are societal changes?\nB: Changes in the whole of society.\nA: Gesellschaftlich or sozial?\nB: Gesellschaftlich is more formal and broader.",funFact:"'Gesellschaft' (society) + '-lich.' More formal than 'sozial.' Gesellschaftlich addresses the structure; sozial addresses the human aspect. 'Gesellschaftliche Ver\u00e4nderungen' (societal changes) shape the big picture."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'Zusammenleben'?",opts:["schnelles Lernen","wirtschaftliche Zusammenarbeit","Koexistenz, gemeinsames Leben","politische Gleichheit"],ans:"Koexistenz, gemeinsames Leben",hint:"Zusammen (together) + a noun for living. Peaceful coexistence. An ongoing project in diverse societies."},
{type:"teach",trg:"multikulturell",src:"multicultural",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Multi' (many) + 'kulturell' (cultural). Germany debated\nfor decades whether it was multikulturell. The answer: yes.",example:"A: Ist Berlin multikulturell?\nB: Absolut. Menschen aus aller Welt.\nA: Eine multikulturelle Stadt lebt von Vielfalt.\nB: Das macht Berlin so besonders.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Berlin multicultural?\nB: Absolutely. People from all over the world.\nA: A multicultural city thrives on diversity.\nB: That is what makes Berlin so special.",funFact:"'Multi' (many) + 'kulturell' (cultural). Germany debated for decades whether it was multikulturell. The answer: yes, whether anyone planned it or not. Berlin is the prime example."},
{type:"teach",trg:"interkulturell",src:"intercultural",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Inter' (between) + 'kulturell.' Between cultures. Multi-\nmeans many cultures existing. Inter- means cultures interacting.",example:"A: Was ist interkulturelle Kompetenz?\nB: Die F\u00e4higkeit, zwischen Kulturen zu vermitteln.\nA: Ist das eine Qualifikation?\nB: Ja, in vielen deutschen Berufen.",exampleSrc:"A: What is intercultural competence?\nB: The ability to mediate between cultures.\nA: Is that a qualification?\nB: Yes, in many German professions.",funFact:"'Inter' (between) + 'kulturell.' 'Interkulturelle Kompetenz' (intercultural competence) is a formal job qualification in Germany. Multi- means many cultures existing. Inter- means cultures interacting."},
{type:"teach",trg:"tolerant",src:"tolerant",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'tolerans.' Same word internationally.\n'Tolerant sein' is easier said than practiced.",example:"A: Bist du tolerant?\nB: Ich versuche es jeden Tag.\nA: Eine tolerante Gesellschaft braucht Arbeit.\nB: Ja, Toleranz kommt nicht von allein.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you tolerant?\nB: I try every day.\nA: A tolerant society requires work.\nB: Yes, tolerance does not come by itself.",funFact:"Nearly every European language uses some version of this word, all tracing back to Latin 'tolerans.' In German, 'tolerant sein' is easier said than practiced. A tolerante Gesellschaft requires daily effort."},
{type:"teach",trg:"traditionell",src:"traditional",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Tradition' + '-ell.' The -ell ending comes from French\nand marks formal adjectives. Can be positive or conservative.",example:"A: Sind das traditionelle Werte?\nB: Ja, seit Generationen.\nA: Traditionell kann positiv sein.\nB: Oder konservativ. Kommt auf den Kontext an.",exampleSrc:"A: Are those traditional values?\nB: Yes, for generations.\nA: Traditional can be positive.\nB: Or conservative. Depends on the context.",funFact:"'Tradition' + '-ell.' The -ell ending comes from French and marks formal adjectives. Traditionell can be positive (heritage) or conservative (resistance to change)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Eine {1} Gesellschaft akzeptiert Unterschiede und behandelt alle gleich.",a:["tolerante"],opts:["traditionelle","interkulturelle","multikulturelle","tolerante"],hint:"The adjective from Latin 'tolerans.' Full acceptance of differences. Easier said than practiced.",sSrc:"A tolerant society accepts differences and treats everyone equally."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reflektieren",src:"to reflect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'reflectere' (to bend back). Both literal (light)\nand figurative (thought). Non-separable -ieren verb.",example:"A: Worauf reflektierst du?\nB: \u00dcber meine Identit\u00e4t.\nA: Es ist wichtig, zu reflektieren.\nB: Ja, besonders in einer neuen Kultur.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you reflecting on?\nB: On my identity.\nA: It is important to reflect.\nB: Yes, especially in a new culture.",funFact:"Light bends back off a mirror. Thoughts bend back on themselves. Both senses come from Latin 'reflectere' (to bend back). A non-separable -ieren verb used for deep thinking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wahrnehmen",src:"to perceive, to notice",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Wahr' (true) + 'nehmen' (to take). Separable: 'Ich nehme\nwahr.' Taking in what is true. Active observation.",example:"A: Nimmst du die Unterschiede wahr?\nB: Ja, jeden Tag.\nA: Die Umgebung bewusst wahrnehmen ist wichtig.\nB: Das ver\u00e4ndert die Perspektive.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you perceive the differences?\nB: Yes, every day.\nA: Consciously perceiving your surroundings is important.\nB: It changes the perspective.",funFact:"'Wahr' (true) + 'nehmen' (to take). Separable: 'Ich nehme wahr.' Taking in what is true. Active observation. The noun Wahrnehmung is one of Germany's great philosophical words."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hinterfragen",src:"to question critically, to scrutinize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Hinter' (behind) + 'fragen' (to ask). Not separable despite\nhinter-. You ask behind the surface. Going deeper.",example:"A: Sollte man Traditionen hinterfragen?\nB: Ja, immer.\nA: Hinterfragen bedeutet nicht ablehnen.\nB: Genau. Es bedeutet verstehen wollen.",exampleSrc:"A: Should one question traditions critically?\nB: Yes, always.\nA: Questioning critically does not mean rejecting.\nB: Exactly. It means wanting to understand.",funFact:"'Hinter' (behind) + 'fragen' (to ask). Not separable despite hinter-. You ask behind the surface. Going deeper than a simple Frage. 'Traditionen hinterfragen' (to question traditions critically)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Interkulturelle Kompetenz ist die Fähigkeit, zwischen Kulturen zu {1}.",a:["vermitteln"],opts:["vermitteln","hinterfragen","reflektieren","wahrnehmen"],hint:"Being the middle person. Building bridges between different worlds. From 'Mittel' (middle/means).",sSrc:"Intercultural competence is the ability to mediate between cultures."},
{type:"mc",q:"Yilmaz sagt: 'Wer seine Herkunft kennt, versteht die Welt besser.' Was bedeutet Herkunft?",opts:["Identität und Selbstbild","Herkunft, Abstammung","Tradition","Vorurteil"],ans:"Herkunft, Abstammung",hint:"Where you come from. 'Her' (from) + 'Kunft' (coming). Your origin and your roots."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius denkt \u00fcber Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit nach. Das bedeutet...",opts:["Bewusstsein, die kognitive Fähigkeit Dinge wahrzunehmen","Wahrnehmung, wie man die Welt sieht","Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit, das Gef\u00fchl dazuzugeh\u00f6ren","Toleranz, andere ausdrücklich zu akzeptieren"],ans:"Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit, das Gef\u00fchl dazuzugeh\u00f6ren",hint:"The abstract noun for belonging. The feeling of being part of a group or community."},
{type:"fb",s:"In einer multikulturellen Gesellschaft ist {1} besonders wichtig.",a:["Toleranz"],opts:["Bankrott","Konjunktur","Inflation","Toleranz"],hint:"The Latin-derived word for acceptance of differences. Lessing wrote about it.",sSrc:"In a multicultural society, tolerance is especially important."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l2",title:"Wer bin ich?",icon:"\uD83E\uDDD0",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Wer bin ich?",desc:"Build a vocabulary of values, beliefs, and worldviews. Understand the philosophical concepts that Germans debate.",goals:["Learn core vocabulary for values and beliefs","Understand philosophical concepts in German","Articulate your own values"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Anschauung",src:"view, perspective, worldview",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'An' (at) + 'Schauung' (viewing). 'Weltanschauung' (worldview)\nis one of Germany's most famous word exports.",example:"A: Was ist deine Anschauung?\nB: Ich glaube an Toleranz und Offenheit.\nA: Eine positive Anschauung.\nB: Ja, gepr\u00e4gt durch Erfahrung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your view?\nB: I believe in tolerance and openness.\nA: A positive worldview.\nB: Yes, shaped by experience.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'Schauung' (viewing). 'Weltanschauung' (worldview) is one of Germany's most famous exports. Kant used Anschauung as a philosophical term for intuitive perception."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die \u00dcberzeugung",src:"conviction, firm belief",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'\u00dcber' (over) + 'Zeugung' (producing). Literally: producing\nsomething overwhelming. Stronger than Meinung (opinion).",example:"A: Handelst du aus \u00dcberzeugung?\nB: Ja, immer.\nA: \u00dcberzeugung gibt Kraft.\nB: Ohne \u00dcberzeugung ist man orientierungslos.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you act from conviction?\nB: Yes, always.\nA: Conviction gives strength.\nB: Without conviction one is disoriented.",funFact:"'\u00dcber' (over) + 'Zeugung' (producing). Literally: producing something overwhelming. 'Aus \u00dcberzeugung handeln' (to act from conviction). Stronger than Meinung (opinion)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vorstellung",src:"concept, idea, imagination",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"COMPOUND: Vor (before/forward) + Stellung (placing).\n'Vor' (before) + 'Stellung' (position). At B2 level, the\nabstract meaning dominates: your idea of something.",example:"A: Was ist deine Vorstellung von Gl\u00fcck?\nB: Zeit mit der Familie.\nA: Jeder hat andere Vorstellungen.\nB: Das macht das Leben interessant.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your idea of happiness?\nB: Time with family.\nA: Everyone has different ideas.\nB: That makes life interesting.",funFact:"'Vor' (before) + 'Stellung' (position). Already known as 'introduction/interview' from B1. At B2: the abstract meaning dominates. 'Meine Vorstellung von Gl\\u00fcck' (my idea of happiness)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er handelt immer aus {1}, nie aus Berechnung.",a:["\u00dcberzeugung"],opts:["\u00dcberzeugung","Vorstellung","Anschauung","Philosophie"],hint:"Stronger than Meinung (opinion). From über + Zeugung. A firm, deeply held belief that drives action.",sSrc:"He always acts from conviction, never from calculation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wertvorstellung",src:"value system, moral conception",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Wert' (value) + 'Vorstellung' (concept). No Fugenelement\nbetween the parts. Your ideas about what matters most.",example:"A: Welche Wertvorstellungen hast du?\nB: Ehrlichkeit und Respekt.\nA: Wertvorstellungen pr\u00e4gen unser Handeln.\nB: Ja, sie sind unser innerer Kompass.",exampleSrc:"A: What values do you hold?\nB: Honesty and respect.\nA: Values shape our actions.\nB: Yes, they are our inner compass.",funFact:"'Wert' (value) + 'Vorstellung' (concept). The Fugen-absence here is noteworthy: Wert + Vorstellung without a connecting element. Your ideas about what matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Selbstbild",src:"self-image",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"'Selbst' (self) + 'Bild' (image). Contrast: Fremdbild (how\nothers see you). The gap between the two is where crises live.",example:"A: Stimmt dein Selbstbild mit der Realit\u00e4t \u00fcberein?\nB: Nicht immer.\nA: Das Selbstbild ver\u00e4ndert sich.\nB: Ja, mit jeder neuen Erfahrung.",exampleSrc:"A: Does your self-image match reality?\nB: Not always.\nA: Self-image changes.\nB: Yes, with every new experience.",funFact:"'Selbst' (self) + 'Bild' (image). 'Sein Selbstbild ver\u00e4ndern' (to change one's self-image). Contrast: Fremdbild (how others see you). The gap between the two is where identity crises live."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Konzept",src:"concept, plan",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'conceptum' (something conceived). In German,\nKonzept also means 'rough draft.' Both senses: something formed.",example:"A: Hast du ein Konzept?\nB: Ja, f\u00fcr das Projekt.\nA: Ein gutes Konzept braucht Zeit.\nB: Aber es spart sp\u00e4ter Arbeit.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a concept?\nB: Yes, for the project.\nA: A good concept takes time.\nB: But it saves work later.",funFact:"Did you know Konzept also means 'rough draft' in German? Both senses share the idea of something taking shape, traced back to Latin 'conceptum' (something conceived)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie man sich selbst sieht, nennt man das...",opts:["Konzept","Selbstbild","Vorstellung","Anschauung"],ans:"Selbstbild",hint:"Selbst (self) + Bild (image). The contrast word is Fremdbild (how others see you)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Philosophie",src:"philosophy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Greek 'philosophia' (love of wisdom). Germany produced\nKant, Hegel, Marx, Nietzsche, Heidegger, Arendt.",example:"A: Interessierst du dich f\u00fcr Philosophie?\nB: Ja, besonders deutsche Philosophie.\nA: Welcher Philosoph inspiriert dich?\nB: Hannah Arendt. Sie dachte radikal.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you interested in philosophy?\nB: Yes, especially German philosophy.\nA: Which philosopher inspires you?\nB: Hannah Arendt. She thought radically.",funFact:"Germany produced Kant, Hegel, Marx, Nietzsche, Heidegger, and Arendt. The Greek root 'philosophia' means love of wisdom, and 'Deutsche Philosophie' is a major academic tradition worldwide."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ethik",src:"ethics",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Greek 'ethike' (moral philosophy). 'Ethik-Kommission'\nreviews medical research and AI projects in Germany.",example:"A: Was ist Ethik?\nB: Die Lehre vom richtigen Handeln.\nA: Brauchen wir Ethik in der Technik?\nB: Unbedingt. Ohne Ethik ist Fortschritt gef\u00e4hrlich.",exampleSrc:"A: What is ethics?\nB: The study of right action.\nA: Do we need ethics in technology?\nB: Absolutely. Without ethics, progress is dangerous.",funFact:"In Germany, an Ethik-Kommission (ethics committee) reviews medical research and AI projects. The word traces to Greek 'ethike' (moral philosophy). Berufsethik (professional ethics) is taken very seriously."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Grundwert",src:"fundamental value",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Grund' (foundation) + 'Wert' (value). The Grundwerte of\nthe Grundgesetz: human dignity, freedom, equality.",example:"A: Was sind die Grundwerte Deutschlands?\nB: Menschenw\u00fcrde, Freiheit, Gleichheit.\nA: Grundwerte sind nicht verhandelbar.\nB: Genau, sie sind die Basis von allem.",exampleSrc:"A: What are Germany's fundamental values?\nB: Human dignity, freedom, equality.\nA: Fundamental values are non-negotiable.\nB: Exactly, they are the basis of everything.",funFact:"'Grund' (foundation) + 'Wert' (value). 'Die Grundwerte des Grundgesetzes' (the fundamental values of the constitution): human dignity, freedom, equality. Foundation values that cannot be changed."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} des Grundgesetzes sind Menschenwürde, Freiheit und Gleichheit.",a:["Grundwerte"],opts:["Konzepte","Anschauungen","Grundwerte","Philosophien"],hint:"Grund (foundation) + Werte (values). The non-negotiable principles enshrined in the constitution.",sSrc:"The fundamental values of the constitution are human dignity, freedom, and equality."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l2b",title:"Wer bin ich? (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83E\uDDD0",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Wer bin ich? (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lebensqualit\u00e4t",src:"quality of life",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Leben' (life) + 's' (Fugen-s) + 'Qualit\u00e4t' (quality).\nGerman cities regularly rank among the highest worldwide.",example:"A: Wie ist die Lebensqualit\u00e4t in Berlin?\nB: Hoch, trotz der Hektik.\nA: Was macht gute Lebensqualit\u00e4t aus?\nB: Gr\u00fcn, Kultur und bezahlbare Mieten.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the quality of life in Berlin?\nB: High, despite the hustle.\nA: What makes good quality of life?\nB: Green spaces, culture, and affordable rent.",funFact:"'Leben' (life) + 's' (Fugen-s) + 'Qualit\u00e4t' (quality). The Fugen-s connects the two parts. German cities regularly rank among the highest for Lebensqualit\u00e4t worldwide."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Menschenw\u00fcrde",src:"human dignity",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Menschen' (human) + 'W\u00fcrde' (dignity). Article 1 of the\nGerman constitution: 'Die W\u00fcrde des Menschen ist unantastbar.'",example:"A: Was ist Menschenw\u00fcrde?\nB: Das Recht, als Mensch respektiert zu werden.\nA: Ist Menschenw\u00fcrde im Grundgesetz?\nB: Ja, Artikel 1. Der wichtigste Satz.",exampleSrc:"A: What is human dignity?\nB: The right to be respected as a human being.\nA: Is human dignity in the constitution?\nB: Yes, Article 1. The most important sentence.",funFact:"'Menschen' (human) + 'W\u00fcrde' (dignity). Article 1 of the German constitution: 'Die W\u00fcrde des Menschen ist unantastbar' (Human dignity is inviolable). The most important sentence in German law."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eigenst\u00e4ndig",src:"independent, autonomous",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Eigen' (own) + 'st\u00e4ndig' (standing). You stand on your own.\nNot relying on others for your opinions or identity.",example:"A: Denkst du eigenst\u00e4ndig?\nB: Ich versuche es immer.\nA: Eigenst\u00e4ndiges Denken ist wichtig.\nB: Besonders in einer Demokratie.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you think independently?\nB: I always try to.\nA: Independent thinking is important.\nB: Especially in a democracy.",funFact:"'Eigen' (own) + 'st\u00e4ndig' (standing). 'Eigenst\u00e4ndig denken' (to think independently). You stand on your own. Not relying on others for your opinions or identity."},
{type:"teach",trg:"offen",src:"open",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Same Germanic root as English 'open.' Karl Popper's\nconcept of the 'open society' deeply influenced Germany.",example:"A: Bist du offen f\u00fcr Neues?\nB: Ja, immer.\nA: Eine offene Gesellschaft braucht offene Menschen.\nB: Da stimme ich voll zu.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you open to new things?\nB: Yes, always.\nA: An open society needs open people.\nB: I fully agree.",funFact:"Same Germanic root as English 'open.' 'Offen f\u00fcr Neues sein' (to be open to new things). Karl Popper's concept of the 'open society' deeply influenced German postwar thought."},
{type:"mc",q:"Artikel 1 des Grundgesetzes schützt die...",opts:["Lebensqualität","Ethik","Tradition","Menschenwürde"],ans:"Menschenwürde",hint:"Menschen (human) + Würde (dignity). The very first sentence of Germany's constitution: inviolable."},
{type:"teach",trg:"respektvoll",src:"respectful",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Respekt' (respect) + 'voll' (full). Full of respect. The\n-voll suffix works like English '-ful': liebevoll, hoffnungsvoll.",example:"A: War das Gespr\u00e4ch respektvoll?\nB: Ja, trotz verschiedener Meinungen.\nA: Respektvoller Umgang ist die Basis.\nB: Ohne Respekt kein Dialog.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the conversation respectful?\nB: Yes, despite different opinions.\nA: Respectful interaction is the basis.\nB: Without respect, no dialogue.",funFact:"'Respekt' (respect) + 'voll' (full). Full of respect. The -voll suffix works like English '-ful': liebevoll (loving), hoffnungsvoll (hopeful), respektvoll (respectful)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"weltoffen",src:"cosmopolitan, open to the world",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Welt' (world) + 'offen' (open). Berlin calls itself weltoffen.\nThe word captures Germany's self-image as globally minded.",example:"A: Ist Hamburg weltoffen?\nB: Ja, als Hafenstadt schon immer.\nA: Weltoffenheit ist eine St\u00e4rke.\nB: Sie kommt vom internationalen Handel.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Hamburg cosmopolitan?\nB: Yes, as a port city, always.\nA: Cosmopolitanism is a strength.\nB: It comes from international trade.",funFact:"'Welt' (world) + 'offen' (open). 'Eine weltoffene Stadt' (a cosmopolitan city). Berlin calls itself weltoffen. The word captures Germany's self-image as globally minded."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vielf\u00e4ltig",src:"diverse, manifold",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Viel' (many) + 'f\u00e4ltig' (fold). Many-folded, multi-layered,\nrich in variety. The adjective form of Vielfalt.",example:"A: Das Programm ist vielf\u00e4ltig.\nB: Ja, f\u00fcr jeden etwas dabei.\nA: Vielf\u00e4ltige Angebote bereichern alle.\nB: Vielfalt ist immer gut.",exampleSrc:"A: The program is diverse.\nB: Yes, something for everyone.\nA: Diverse offerings enrich everyone.\nB: Diversity is always good.",funFact:"'Viel' (many) + 'f\u00e4ltig' (fold). Related to Vielfalt. The adjective form. Many-folded, multi-layered, rich in variety. 'Eine vielf\u00e4ltige Kultur' (a diverse culture)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie nennt man eine Stadt, die offen für die ganze Welt ist?",opts:["weltoffen","vielfältig","eigenständig","respektvoll"],ans:"weltoffen",hint:"Welt (world) + offen (open). Berlin describes itself with this compound adjective."},
{type:"teach",trg:"respektieren",src:"to respect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'respectare' (to look back at). Non-separable\n-ieren verb. Same word across European languages.",example:"A: Respektierst du andere Kulturen?\nB: Selbstverst\u00e4ndlich.\nA: Respektieren bedeutet ernst nehmen.\nB: Ja, nicht nur tolerieren, sondern sch\u00e4tzen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you respect other cultures?\nB: Of course.\nA: Respecting means taking seriously.\nB: Yes, not just tolerating, but valuing.",funFact:"The same word across nearly every European language. Latin 'respectare' literally meant 'to look back at,' implying you value someone enough to give them a second glance."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pr\u00e4gen",src:"to shape, to coin, to imprint",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Die Kindheit pr\u00e4gt den Menschen' (Childhood shapes a person).\nAlso: 'eine M\u00fcnze pr\u00e4gen' (to mint a coin). Deeply formative.",example:"A: Was pr\u00e4gt einen Menschen?\nB: Familie, Kultur und Erfahrungen.\nA: Berlin hat mich gepr\u00e4gt.\nB: Jede Stadt pr\u00e4gt ihre Bewohner.",exampleSrc:"A: What shapes a person?\nB: Family, culture, and experiences.\nA: Berlin has shaped me.\nB: Every city shapes its residents.",funFact:"Something stamped into you that remains. 'Die Kindheit pr\u00e4gt den Menschen' (Childhood shapes a person). Also: 'eine M\u00fcnze pr\u00e4gen' (to mint a coin). Deeply formative."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pflegen",src:"to care for, to maintain, to cultivate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Traditionen pflegen' (to cultivate traditions). Also:\n'Kranke pflegen' (to care for the sick). Nurturing in all forms.",example:"A: Pflegst du deine Traditionen?\nB: Ja, das ist mir wichtig.\nA: Pflegen bedeutet aktiv bewahren.\nB: Genau, nicht nur passiv erinnern.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you maintain your traditions?\nB: Yes, that is important to me.\nA: To maintain means to actively preserve.\nB: Exactly, not just passively remember.",funFact:"'Traditionen pflegen' (to cultivate traditions). Also: 'Kranke pflegen' (to care for the sick). 'Pflegeversicherung' (nursing care insurance) is one of Germany's five social insurances."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anerkennen",src:"to acknowledge, to recognize officially",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'An' (at) + 'erkennen' (to recognize). Not separable despite\nthe an-. The official stamp of acceptance.",example:"A: Wird dein Abschluss anerkannt?\nB: Ja, nach langer Pr\u00fcfung.\nA: Anerkennung ist wichtig f\u00fcr die Karriere.\nB: Ohne Anerkennung geht wenig.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your degree recognized?\nB: Yes, after a long review.\nA: Recognition is important for one's career.\nB: Without recognition, little is possible.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'erkennen' (to recognize). 'Einen Abschluss anerkennen' (to recognize a degree). Not separable despite the an-. The official stamp of acceptance."},
{type:"mc",q:"Menschenw\u00fcrde bedeutet...",opts:["menschliche Qualit\u00e4t, wie moralisch gut ein Mensch ist","menschliche W\u00fcrde, das Recht auf Respekt als Mensch","menschliche Tradition, alte überlieferte Bräuche","menschliche Toleranz, andere zu ertragen"],ans:"menschliche W\u00fcrde, das Recht auf Respekt als Mensch",hint:"A compound noun enshrined in Article 1 of the German constitution. Identify the two root elements: the being and the quality being protected."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Grundwert",src:"fundamental value"},{trg:"\u00dcberzeugung",src:"conviction"},{trg:"Selbstbild",src:"self-image"},{trg:"Ethik",src:"ethics"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Kindheit {1} den Menschen f\u00fcr sein ganzes Leben.",a:["pr\u00e4gt"],opts:["pflegt","anerkennt","pr\u00e4gt","reflektiert"],hint:"To form and shape. Childhood stamps something into a person that stays.",sSrc:"Childhood shapes a person for their whole life."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'respektieren'?",opts:["philosophy","value system, moral conception","to respect","diverse, manifold"],ans:"to respect",hint:"Near-identical in English. From Latin re + spectare (to look back at). To regard something with esteem."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} bedeutet aktiv bewahren.",a:["pflegen"],opts:["pflegen","die Philosophie","die \\u00dcberzeugung","die Vorstellung"],hint:"The verb for actively nurturing something: a garden, a tradition, or a relationship.",sSrc:"To maintain means to actively preserve."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'anerkennen'?",opts:["ethics","self-image","human dignity","to acknowledge, to recognize officially"],ans:"to acknowledge, to recognize officially",hint:"an- + erkennen (to know/discern). To formally accept the validity of something."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l3",title:"Wer seine Herkunft kennt",icon:"\uD83D\uDCDA",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Wer seine Herkunft kennt",desc:"Master generalized relative clauses for universal statements. Discuss migration, integration, and identity in German.",goals:["Learn generalized relative clauses (wer..., der...; alles, was...)","Discuss migration and integration","Build complex argumentative sentences"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Migration",src:"migration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'migratio' (wandering). Germany's 2015\nMigrationsdebatte changed the political landscape.",example:"A: Wie hat Migration Deutschland ver\u00e4ndert?\nB: Grundlegend. 26 Prozent haben Migrationshintergrund.\nA: Migration bringt Vielfalt.\nB: Und Herausforderungen. Beides.",exampleSrc:"A: How has migration changed Germany?\nB: Fundamentally. 26 percent have a migration background.\nA: Migration brings diversity.\nB: And challenges. Both.",funFact:"21 million people in Germany have a 'Migrationshintergrund' (migration background), an official census category. The 2015 Migrationsdebatte reshaped politics. Latin root: 'migratio' (wandering)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Integration",src:"integration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'integratio' (renewal). 'Integration ist keine\nEinbahnstra\u00dfe' (not a one-way street) is a common German saying.",example:"A: Wie gelingt Integration?\nB: Durch Sprache, Arbeit und Respekt.\nA: Integration braucht beide Seiten.\nB: Ja, es ist keine Einbahnstra\u00dfe.",exampleSrc:"A: How does integration succeed?\nB: Through language, work, and respect.\nA: Integration requires both sides.\nB: Yes, it is not a one-way street.",funFact:"'Integration ist keine Einbahnstra\u00dfe' (Integration is not a one-way street) is a widely used saying. Both sides must move. The Latin root 'integratio' originally meant renewal or restoration."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einwanderung",src:"immigration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"COMPOUND: Ein (in) + Wanderung (wandering).\n'Ein' (in) + 'Wanderung' (wandering). Germany was officially\n'kein Einwanderungsland' until 2005. Reality preceded policy.",example:"A: Ist Deutschland ein Einwanderungsland?\nB: Ja, seit 2005 offiziell.\nA: Einwanderung hat Geschichte ver\u00e4ndert.\nB: Millionen Menschen kamen und blieben.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Germany an immigration country?\nB: Yes, officially since 2005.\nA: Immigration has changed history.\nB: Millions of people came and stayed.",funFact:"'Ein' (in) + 'Wanderung' (wandering). Germany was officially 'kein Einwanderungsland' (not a country of immigration) until 2005 when it passed its first immigration law. Reality preceded policy by decades."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Diskriminierung",src:"discrimination",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'discriminare' (to distinguish). The AGG (General\nEqual Treatment Act) of 2006 prohibits it in employment.",example:"A: Hast du Diskriminierung erlebt?\nB: Leider ja.\nA: Diskriminierung ist gesetzlich verboten.\nB: Aber sie existiert trotzdem noch.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you experienced discrimination?\nB: Unfortunately yes.\nA: Discrimination is legally prohibited.\nB: But it still exists despite that.",funFact:"Germany's AGG (General Equal Treatment Act, 2006) explicitly prohibits Diskriminierung in employment and daily life. The Latin root 'discriminare' originally just meant to distinguish."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Inklusion",src:"inclusion",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'inclusio' (enclosure). Beyond disability:\n'Inklusion means everyone belongs.' Active inclusion.",example:"A: Was bedeutet Inklusion?\nB: Alle geh\u00f6ren dazu, ohne Ausnahme.\nA: Inklusion geht weiter als Toleranz.\nB: Ja, es bedeutet aktives Einbeziehen.",exampleSrc:"A: What does inclusion mean?\nB: Everyone belongs, without exception.\nA: Inclusion goes further than tolerance.\nB: Yes, it means actively including.",funFact:"Germany's education system is actively moving toward Inklusion in schools. The Latin root 'inclusio' meant enclosure, but the modern meaning goes beyond disability: everyone belongs. Not tolerance, but active inclusion."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Migration und Einwanderung?",opts:["Migration ist allgemein, Einwanderung betont das Zielland","beide Wörter sind identisch","Migration ist negativ, Einwanderung positiv","Einwanderung ist allgemein, Migration betont das Zielland"],ans:"Migration ist allgemein, Einwanderung betont das Zielland",hint:"One term is general movement across borders; the other specifically highlights where you are going TO."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Milieu",src:"social environment, milieu",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From French 'milieu' (middle/environment). Sinus-Milieus\ndivide German society into lifestyle groups.",example:"A: Aus welchem Milieu kommst du?\nB: Aus einem akademischen Milieu.\nA: Das Milieu pr\u00e4gt die Weltanschauung.\nB: Ja, es formt, wie wir denken.",exampleSrc:"A: What social environment do you come from?\nB: From an academic milieu.\nA: The milieu shapes the worldview.\nB: Yes, it forms how we think.",funFact:"Sinus-Milieus divide German society into lifestyle groups: liberal-intellectual, traditional, performer, and more. Borrowed from French 'milieu' (middle/environment), your Milieu shapes your Weltanschauung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Generationenkonflikt",src:"generational conflict",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Generationen' (generations) + 'Konflikt.' The Fugen-en\nconnects the parts. Every generation has its defining conflict.",example:"A: Gibt es bei euch einen Generationenkonflikt?\nB: Ja, beim Thema Klima.\nA: Jede Generation hat ihren Konflikt.\nB: Die 68er gegen ihre Eltern, wir gegen den Klimawandel.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a generational conflict in your family?\nB: Yes, on the topic of climate.\nA: Every generation has its conflict.\nB: The 68ers against their parents, we against climate change.",funFact:"'Generationen' (generations) + 'Konflikt.' Every generation in Germany has its defining conflict: 68ers vs. parents, Gen Z vs. Boomers on climate. The Fugen-en connects the parts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Wandel",src:"change, transformation",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'wandeln' (to change/walk). Gradual, deep change: not\na revolution but an evolution. Wandel takes time.",example:"A: Siehst du einen gesellschaftlichen Wandel?\nB: Ja, die Gesellschaft wird offener.\nA: Wandel ist langsam, aber stetig.\nB: Besser langsam als gar nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you see societal change?\nB: Yes, society is becoming more open.\nA: Change is slow but steady.\nB: Better slow than not at all.",funFact:"Willy Brandt's famous Ostpolitik slogan was 'Wandel durch Annaeherung' (change through rapprochement). The verb 'wandeln' means both to change and to walk, capturing the idea of gradual, step-by-step transformation."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} einer Gesellschaft verändert sich mit jeder Generation.",a:["Lebensweise"],opts:["Diskriminierung","Lebensweise","Inklusion","Einwanderung"],hint:"Lebens (life's) + Weise (way/manner). How you choose to live. The Fugen-s connects the parts.",sSrc:"The way of life of a society changes with every generation."},
{type:"mc",q:"Beim Thema Klima gibt es einen {blank} zwischen Jungen und Alten.",opts:["Generationenkonflikt","Milieu","Wandel","Lebensweise"],ans:"Generationenkonflikt",hint:"A conflict between different age groups. Generationen (generations) + Konflikt (conflict)."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l3b",title:"Wer seine Herkunft kennt (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83D\uDCDA",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Wer seine Herkunft kennt (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lebensweise",src:"way of life, lifestyle",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Lebens' (life's) + 'Weise' (way/manner). The Fugen-s links\nLeben to Weise. How you choose to live your life.",example:"A: Welche Lebensweise bevorzugst du?\nB: Einfach und bewusst.\nA: Alternative Lebensweisen sind akzeptiert.\nB: In Berlin auf jeden Fall.",exampleSrc:"A: Which lifestyle do you prefer?\nB: Simple and conscious.\nA: Alternative lifestyles are accepted.\nB: In Berlin, definitely.",funFact:"'Lebens' (life's) + 'Weise' (way/manner). The Fugen-s links Leben to Weise. 'Alternative Lebensweisen' (alternative lifestyles) became a political topic in the 1970s."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Weltanschauung",src:"worldview",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"COMPOUND: Welt (world) + Anschauung (view).\n'Welt' (world) + 'Anschauung' (view). One of the most\nfamous German words exported to English. Kant used it first.",example:"A: Was ist deine Weltanschauung?\nB: Humanistisch und weltoffen.\nA: Weltanschauung ist mehr als Meinung.\nB: Ja, es ist ein ganzes Denksystem.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your worldview?\nB: Humanistic and cosmopolitan.\nA: A worldview is more than an opinion.\nB: Yes, it is an entire system of thought.",funFact:"'Welt' (world) + 'Anschauung' (view). One of the most famous German words exported to English. Kant used it first. Your comprehensive framework for understanding everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ethnisch",src:"ethnic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'ethnikos' (of a people). Used carefully in German\ndiscourse due to historical sensitivity.",example:"A: Was bedeutet ethnische Vielfalt?\nB: Menschen verschiedener Herkunft zusammen.\nA: Ethnisch ist ein sensibles Wort.\nB: Ja, man benutzt es vorsichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: What does ethnic diversity mean?\nB: People of different origins together.\nA: Ethnic is a sensitive word.\nB: Yes, one uses it carefully.",funFact:"Due to historical sensitivity, 'ethnisch' is used very carefully in German discourse. The Greek root 'ethnikos' simply meant 'of a people,' but the word carries extra weight in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pluralistisch",src:"pluralistic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Plural' + '-istisch.' Many worldviews coexisting. The ideal\nof the Grundgesetz: no single ideology dominates.",example:"A: Ist Deutschland pluralistisch?\nB: Ja, viele Meinungen koexistieren.\nA: Eine pluralistische Gesellschaft braucht Dialog.\nB: Und die Bereitschaft zuzuh\u00f6ren.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Germany pluralistic?\nB: Yes, many opinions coexist.\nA: A pluralistic society needs dialogue.\nB: And the willingness to listen.",funFact:"'Plural' + '-istisch.' Pluralistic. Many worldviews coexisting. The ideal of the Grundgesetz: no single ideology dominates. 'Eine pluralistische Gesellschaft' (a pluralistic society)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kosmopolitisch",src:"cosmopolitan",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'kosmopolites' (citizen of the world). Berlin\nconsiders itself kosmopolitisch. Comfort with global diversity.",example:"A: F\u00fchlst du dich kosmopolitisch?\nB: In Berlin auf jeden Fall.\nA: Kosmopolitisch bedeutet weltoffen leben.\nB: Ja, sich in der Welt zu Hause f\u00fchlen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel cosmopolitan?\nB: In Berlin, definitely.\nA: Cosmopolitan means living open to the world.\nB: Yes, feeling at home in the world.",funFact:"Berlin proudly considers itself kosmopolitisch. The word goes back to Greek 'kosmopolites' (citizen of the world) and implies genuine comfort with global diversity, not just exposure to it."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort beschreibt jemanden, der sich in der ganzen Welt zu Hause fuehlt?",opts:["pluralistisch","ethnisch","kosmopolitisch","interkulturell"],ans:"kosmopolitisch",hint:"From Greek 'kosmopolites' (citizen of the world). Comfort with global diversity."},
{type:"teach",trg:"integrieren",src:"to integrate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'integrare' (to make whole). Non-separable -ieren\nverb. Both transitive and reflexive.",example:"A: Wie kann man sich integrieren?\nB: Sprache lernen und teilnehmen.\nA: Integration beginnt mit dem Wollen.\nB: Und mit der Offenheit der Gesellschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: How can one integrate?\nB: Learn the language and participate.\nA: Integration begins with wanting to.\nB: And with the openness of society.",funFact:"The Latin root 'integrare' meant to make whole. As a reflexive verb, 'sich integrieren' means to become part of a society. As transitive: 'Menschen integrieren' means to welcome them in."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich auseinandersetzen mit",src:"to engage critically with, to confront",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Auseinander' (apart) + 'setzen' (to set) + 'mit' (with).\nLiterally: to set things apart with something. Intellectual verb.",example:"A: Setzt du dich mit Vorurteilen auseinander?\nB: Ja, aktiv.\nA: Sich auseinandersetzen bedeutet kritisch pr\u00fcfen.\nB: Nicht einfach akzeptieren, sondern hinterfragen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you engage critically with prejudices?\nB: Yes, actively.\nA: To engage critically means to examine.\nB: Not simply accept, but question.",funFact:"'Auseinander' (apart) + 'setzen' (to set) + 'mit' (with). Literally: to set things apart with something. 'Sich mit Vorurteilen auseinandersetzen' (to confront prejudices). The most intellectual reflexive verb in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich identifizieren mit",src:"to identify with",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Identifizieren' (to identify) + 'mit' (with). Reflexive.\nFinding yourself in something external.",example:"A: Identifizierst du dich mit Berlin?\nB: Ja, die Stadt ist Teil von mir geworden.\nA: Sich identifizieren bedeutet sich zugeh\u00f6rig f\u00fchlen.\nB: Genau, es ist ein Gef\u00fchl der Verbindung.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you identify with Berlin?\nB: Yes, the city has become part of me.\nA: To identify with means to feel belonging.\nB: Exactly, it is a feeling of connection.",funFact:"'Identifizieren' (to identify) + 'mit' (with). Reflexive. 'Sich mit einer Kultur identifizieren' (to identify with a culture). Finding yourself in something external."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Adjektiv beschreibt eine Gesellschaft mit vielen verschiedenen Weltanschauungen?",opts:["ethnisch","kosmopolitisch","interkulturell","pluralistisch"],ans:"pluralistisch",hint:"Plural + -istisch. Many worldviews coexisting. The ideal of the Grundgesetz."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich anpassen",src:"to adapt, to adjust",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'An' (at/to) + 'passen' (to fit). Separable and reflexive.\nFitting yourself to new circumstances without losing yourself.",example:"A: Passt du dich schnell an?\nB: Ja, das musste ich lernen.\nA: Sich anpassen ist nicht sich aufgeben.\nB: Richtig. Anpassen und bewahren gleichzeitig.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you adapt quickly?\nB: Yes, I had to learn that.\nA: Adapting is not giving up who you are.\nB: Right. Adapting and preserving at the same time.",funFact:"'An' (at/to) + 'passen' (to fit). Separable: 'Ich passe mich an.' Fitting yourself to new circumstances. Not losing yourself, but adjusting. A survival skill."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vermitteln",src:"to mediate, to convey",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Ver-' + 'Mittel' (middle/means). Being the middle person.\nAlso: 'Wissen vermitteln' (to convey knowledge). A bridge function.",example:"A: Kannst du zwischen den Kulturen vermitteln?\nB: Das versuche ich jeden Tag.\nA: Vermitteln bedeutet Br\u00fccken bauen.\nB: Ja, zwischen verschiedenen Welten.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you mediate between cultures?\nB: I try that every day.\nA: To mediate means to build bridges.\nB: Yes, between different worlds.",funFact:"'Ver-' + 'Mittel' (middle/means). 'Zwischen Kulturen vermitteln' (to mediate between cultures). Being the middle person. Also: 'Wissen vermitteln' (to convey knowledge). A bridge function."},
{type:"tip",title:"Verallgemeinerte Relativs\u00e4tze: wer..., der...",text:"German has special relative clauses for universal statements. No specific person, but anyone who fits.\n\nwer..., der...: 'Wer tolerant ist, der gewinnt Freunde.'\n(Whoever is tolerant gains friends.)\n\nwas..., das...: 'Was er sagt, das stimmt.'\n(What he says is true.)\n\nalles, was...: 'Alles, was ich erlebt habe, hat mich geformt.'\n(Everything I experienced shaped me.)\n\nnichts, was...: 'Nichts, was er sagt, \u00fcberrascht mich.'\n(Nothing he says surprises me.)\n\ndas, was...: 'Das, was z\u00e4hlt, ist Respekt.'\n(That which counts is respect.)\n\nThe wer-clause is a free relative clause: no antecedent noun needed. The verb goes to the end of the relative clause.",deepDive:{title:"Case in generalizing relative clauses",text:"Wer, wen, wem function like relative pronouns:\n\nNominative: Wer tolerant ist, der gewinnt.\nAccusative: Wen man respektiert, den hoert man.\nDative: Wem man hilft, dem hilft man gern.\n\nThe demonstrative pronoun in the main clause (der/den/dem) can be dropped:\n'Wer tolerant ist, gewinnt Freunde.' (also correct)\n\nAfter alles, nichts, etwas, das, always use 'was' (not 'das'):\n'Alles, was zaehlt' (not: 'Alles, das zaehlt')"}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Verallgemeinerte Relativs\u00e4tze: Muster",groups:[{label:"wer..., der... (wer auch immer)",rows:[{pronoun:"wer (Nom)",form:"Wer tolerant ist, der gewinnt.",src:"Whoever is tolerant, wins."},{pronoun:"wen (Akk)",form:"Wen man respektiert, den h\u00f6rt man.",src:"Whomever one respects, one listens to."},{pronoun:"wem (Dat)",form:"Wem man hilft, dem hilft man gern.",src:"Whomever one helps, one helps gladly."}]},{label:"was/alles/nichts/das (was/alles/nichts/das, was)",rows:[{pronoun:"was",form:"Was z\u00e4hlt, ist Respekt.",src:"What counts is respect."},{pronoun:"alles, was",form:"Alles, was er sagt, stimmt.",src:"Everything he says is true."},{pronoun:"nichts, was",form:"Nichts, was passiert, ist Zufall.",src:"Nothing that happens is coincidence."},{pronoun:"das, was",form:"Das, was bleibt, ist Erinnerung.",src:"That which remains is memory."}]}],note:"Wer/wen/wem folgen den Kasusregeln. Nach alles/nichts/etwas/das immer 'was,' nie 'das.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Heinrich sagt: 'Wer richtig spricht, der wird auch richtig verstanden.' Was bedeutet 'wer' hier?",opts:["wer (eine bestimmte Person)","wer auch immer, jeder der","wo (Ortsangabe)","wann (Zeitangabe)"],ans:"wer auch immer, jeder der",hint:"Without a reference word, this pronoun becomes universal: 'whoever' or 'anyone who.' A general truth."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} seine Herkunft kennt, der versteht sich selbst besser.",a:["Wer"],opts:["Der","Was","Wer","Welcher"],hint:"A relative pronoun for universal statements, not referring to a specific person. It opens a free relative clause followed by 'der' in the main clause.",sSrc:"Whoever knows their heritage understands themselves better."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'sich auseinandersetzen mit'?",opts:["to engage critically with, to confront","ethnic","migration","social environment, milieu"],ans:"to engage critically with, to confront",hint:"auseinander (apart) + setzen (to set) + sich (oneself) + mit (with). To sit down and wrestle with a topic."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to identify with' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["sich identifizieren mit"],opts:["integrieren","sich identifizieren mit","die Integration","kosmopolitisch"],hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. Reflexive: to see oneself as part of something.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to identify with' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'sich anpassen'?",opts:["integration","way of life, lifestyle","to adapt, to adjust","to integrate"],ans:"to adapt, to adjust",hint:"sich (oneself) + an- (to) + passen (to fit). To make yourself fit a new environment."},
{type:"fb",s:"Kannst du zwischen den Kulturen {1}?",a:["vermitteln"],opts:["ethnisch","sich auseinandersetzen mit","die Migration","vermitteln"],hint:"From Mitte (middle). To stand between two sides and bridge the gap.",sSrc:"Can you mediate between cultures?"}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l4",title:"Dieser und jener",icon:"\uD83D\uDD0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Dieser und jener",desc:"Master reference words for precise reference in German. Build text cohesion in written and formal language.",goals:["Learn reference words: dieser, jener, solcher, derjenige, derselbe","Distinguish similar items with elegance","Build logical discourse with ersterer/letzterer"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"dieser",src:"this one, this",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Refers to something near or just mentioned. Declines like\na der-word: dieser/diese/dieses/diese. Most common Verweiswort.",example:"A: Welches Buch meinst du?\nB: Dieses hier.\nA: Dieser Wert ist mir wichtig.\nB: Mir auch. Dieser Wert verbindet uns.",exampleSrc:"A: Which book do you mean?\nB: This one here.\nA: This value is important to me.\nB: To me too. This value connects us.",funFact:"Refers to something near or just mentioned. 'Dieser Wert ist wichtig' (This value is important). Declines like a der-word: dieser/diese/dieses/diese. The most common Verweiswort."},
{type:"teach",trg:"jener",src:"that one (distant)",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Points to something farther away or previously mentioned.\nDeclines like dieser. More literary than spoken.",example:"A: Kennst du jenen K\u00fcnstler?\nB: Jenen aus dem 19. Jahrhundert?\nA: Ja, jener hat hier gelebt.\nB: Jene Zeit war faszinierend.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know that artist?\nB: That one from the 19th century?\nA: Yes, that one lived here.\nB: That era was fascinating.",funFact:"Points to something farther away or previously mentioned. 'Jener K\u00fcnstler lebte im 19. Jahrhundert' (That artist lived in the 19th century). Declines like dieser. More literary than spoken."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Diese Skulptur ist griechisch. Jene ist ägyptisch.' Was zeigt 'jener' an?",opts:["etwas Nahes","etwas Entferntes oder zuvor Erwaentes","etwas Identisches","eine Art oder Sorte"],ans:"etwas Entferntes oder zuvor Erwaentes",hint:"The counterpart to 'dieser' (this). Points to something farther away or previously mentioned. More literary."},
{type:"teach",trg:"solcher",src:"such a one, such",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Describes a kind or type. Declines like dieser. 'Solch ein\nMensch' inverts: solch + ein + noun.",example:"A: Solche Vorurteile sind gef\u00e4hrlich.\nB: Ja, solche Denkweisen m\u00fcssen sich \u00e4ndern.\nA: Solch ein Mensch inspiriert mich.\nB: Solche Menschen braucht die Welt.",exampleSrc:"A: Such prejudices are dangerous.\nB: Yes, such ways of thinking must change.\nA: Such a person inspires me.\nB: The world needs such people.",funFact:"Describes a kind or type. 'Solche Vorurteile sind gef\u00e4hrlich' (Such prejudices are dangerous). Declines like dieser. 'Solch ein Mensch' (such a person) inverts: solch + ein + noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"derjenige",src:"the one who (masculine)",pos:"pron",gender:"m",note:"'Der' + 'jenige' (the particular one). Compound demonstrative.\nBoth parts decline: desjenigen, demjenigen.",example:"A: Derjenige, der zuerst kommt, gewinnt.\nB: Wer ist derjenige?\nA: Derjenige, der am h\u00e4rtesten arbeitet.\nB: Dann muss ich mich beeilen.",exampleSrc:"A: The one who comes first wins.\nB: Who is the one?\nA: The one who works the hardest.\nB: Then I need to hurry.",funFact:"'Der' + 'jenige' (the particular one). 'Derjenige, der zuerst kommt, gewinnt' (The one who comes first wins). Compound demonstrative. Both parts decline: desjenigen, demjenigen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"diejenige",src:"the one who (feminine)",pos:"pron",gender:"f",note:"Feminine form of derjenige. Both parts decline together.\nFormal, written register.",example:"A: Diejenige, die am meisten liest, wei\u00df am meisten.\nB: Ist das Yilmaz?\nA: Ja, diejenige, die immer ein Buch dabei hat.\nB: Stimmt, sie liest st\u00e4ndig.",exampleSrc:"A: The one who reads the most knows the most.\nB: Is that Yilmaz?\nA: Yes, the one who always has a book with her.\nB: True, she reads constantly.",funFact:"Feminine form of derjenige. 'Diejenige, die am meisten liest, wei\u00df am meisten' (The one (f.) who reads the most knows the most). Both parts decline together."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dasjenige",src:"the one which (neuter)",pos:"pron",gender:"n",note:"Neuter form of derjenige. Formal, written. In speech,\nGermans often substitute 'das, was.'",example:"A: Dasjenige, was wirklich z\u00e4hlt, ist Respekt.\nB: Stimmt. Dasjenige Buch m\u00f6chte ich lesen.\nA: Dasjenige Kind, das dort spielt?\nB: Ja, dasjenige mit dem roten Hut.",exampleSrc:"A: That which truly counts is respect.\nB: True. I would like to read that book.\nA: That child playing over there?\nB: Yes, the one with the red hat.",funFact:"Neuter form of derjenige. 'Dasjenige, was wirklich z\u00e4hlt' (That which truly counts). Formal, written. In speech, Germans often substitute 'das, was.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"{1}, der mutig ist, wird immer einen Weg finden.",a:["Derjenige"],opts:["Derjenige","Dieser","Jener","Solcher"],hint:"A compound demonstrative that singles out a specific person. Both parts decline. Used with a relative clause.",sSrc:"The one who is brave will always find a way."},
{type:"teach",trg:"derselbe",src:"the same one (masculine)",pos:"pron",gender:"m",note:"'Der' + 'selbe' (same). Both parts decline. Implies true\nidentity: literally the same individual or thing.",example:"A: Ist das derselbe Mann?\nB: Ja, derselbe wie gestern.\nA: Derselbe Fehler passiert immer wieder.\nB: Wir m\u00fcssen daraus lernen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that the same man?\nB: Yes, the same one as yesterday.\nA: The same mistake happens again and again.\nB: We must learn from it.",funFact:"'Der' + 'selbe' (same). Both parts decline. Derselbe implies true identity: literally the same individual or thing. 'Derselbe Fehler passiert immer wieder' (The same mistake happens again and again)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dieselbe",src:"the same one (feminine)",pos:"pron",gender:"f",note:"Feminine form of derselbe. Not 'die gleiche' (the similar one).\nDerselbe = identical. Der gleiche = similar but separate.",example:"A: Dieselbe Frage stellt sich jede Generation.\nB: Ja, immer dieselbe.\nA: Ist es dieselbe oder nur die gleiche?\nB: Dieselbe: identisch. Die gleiche: \u00e4hnlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Every generation faces the same question.\nB: Yes, always the same one.\nA: Is it the same or just a similar one?\nB: Dieselbe: identical. Die gleiche: similar.",funFact:"Feminine form of derselbe. 'Dieselbe Frage stellt sich jede Generation' (Every generation faces the same question). Not to be confused with 'die gleiche' (the similar one). Derselbe = identical."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dasselbe",src:"the same one (neuter)",pos:"pron",gender:"n",note:"Neuter form of derselbe. 'Ist das dasselbe oder nur das\nGleiche?' is a famous German distinction.",example:"A: Ist das dasselbe?\nB: Nein, nur das Gleiche.\nA: Dasselbe Gef\u00fchl hatte ich auch.\nB: Wir teilen dasselbe Erlebnis.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that the same thing?\nB: No, just a similar one.\nA: I had the same feeling too.\nB: We share the same experience.",funFact:"Neuter form of derselbe. 'Ist das dasselbe oder nur das Gleiche?' (Is it the same or just similar?) A famous German distinction. Dasselbe = one and the same object. Das Gleiche = two objects that look alike."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ersterer",src:"the former",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"'Erster' (first) + comparative ending. Used in formal writing\nto refer back to the first of two things mentioned.",example:"A: Toleranz und Respekt: Ersterer ist passiv, letzterer aktiv.\nB: Guter Vergleich.\nA: Ersterer akzeptiert, letzterer sch\u00e4tzt.\nB: Beides ist wichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: Tolerance and respect: the former is passive, the latter active.\nB: Good comparison.\nA: The former accepts, the latter values.\nB: Both are important.",funFact:"'Erster' (first) + comparative ending. 'Toleranz und Respekt: Ersterer ist passiv, letzterer aktiv.' Used in formal writing to refer back to two things. Shows you can track two referents across a sentence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"letzterer",src:"the latter",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"'Letzter' (last) + comparative ending. Classic academic\npairing with ersterer. Avoids repeating nouns. Written register.",example:"A: Kultur und Sprache: Letztere verbindet Menschen.\nB: Und erstere pr\u00e4gt sie.\nA: Ersterer... letzterer... ist elegant.\nB: Ja, besonders in akademischen Texten.",exampleSrc:"A: Culture and language: the latter connects people.\nB: And the former shapes them.\nA: The former... the latter... is elegant.\nB: Yes, especially in academic texts.",funFact:"'Letzter' (last) + comparative ending. 'Ersterer... letzterer...' is a classic academic pairing. It avoids repeating nouns. Written register. Shows sophisticated text cohesion."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ist das dasselbe Buch oder nur das Gleiche?' Was ist der Unterschied?",opts:["dasselbe = identisch, das Gleiche = ähnlich","dasselbe = ähnlich, das Gleiche = identisch","kein Unterschied, beide sind synonym","dasselbe ist formal, das Gleiche ist informal"],ans:"dasselbe = identisch, das Gleiche = ähnlich",hint:"One refers to a single, identical object shared by all references. The other allows for two separate but equivalent objects."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l4b",title:"Dieser und jener (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83D\uDD0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Dieser und jener (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"ein solcher",src:"such a (one)",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"'Ein' + 'solcher.' The indefinite article version of solcher.\nEin solcher Mensch = a person of that kind.",example:"A: Ein solcher Wandel braucht Zeit.\nB: Ja, ein solcher Prozess ist langsam.\nA: Ein solcher Mensch inspiriert mich.\nB: Solche Menschen sind selten.",exampleSrc:"A: Such a change takes time.\nB: Yes, such a process is slow.\nA: Such a person inspires me.\nB: Such people are rare.",funFact:"'Ein' + 'solcher.' The indefinite article version of solcher. 'Ein solcher Wandel braucht Zeit' (Such a change takes time). Ein solcher Mensch = a person of that kind."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gleicherma\u00dfen",src:"equally, in equal measure",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Gleicher' (equal) + 'Ma\u00dfen' (measure). An elegant adverb\nfor balanced comparisons in formal writing.",example:"A: Alle profitieren gleicherma\u00dfen.\nB: Das ist das Ziel.\nA: Gleicherma\u00dfen wichtig sind Toleranz und Respekt.\nB: Ja, beides gleicherma\u00dfen.",exampleSrc:"A: Everyone benefits equally.\nB: That is the goal.\nA: Equally important are tolerance and respect.\nB: Yes, both equally.",funFact:"'Gleicher' (equal) + 'Ma\u00dfen' (measure). 'Alle profitieren gleicherma\u00dfen' (Everyone benefits equally). An elegant adverb for balanced comparisons."},
{type:"teach",trg:"im Wesentlichen",src:"essentially, in essence",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Im' + 'Wesentlichen' (essential). A qualifier that focuses\non the core. Allows for minor disagreements.",example:"A: Stimmst du zu?\nB: Im Wesentlichen ja.\nA: Im Wesentlichen sind wir einer Meinung.\nB: Nur in Details gibt es Unterschiede.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you agree?\nB: Essentially yes.\nA: Essentially we are of one opinion.\nB: Only in details are there differences.",funFact:"'Im' + 'Wesentlichen' (essential). 'Im Wesentlichen stimme ich zu' (I essentially agree). A qualifier that focuses on the core. Allows for minor disagreements."},
{type:"teach",trg:"im Grunde",src:"fundamentally, basically",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Im' + 'Grunde' (ground/foundation). Looks at the foundation\nbeneath the surface. What lies at the very bottom.",example:"A: Im Grunde sind alle Menschen gleich.\nB: Ja, im Grunde schon.\nA: Im Grunde wollen wir alle dasselbe.\nB: Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit und Respekt.",exampleSrc:"A: Fundamentally, all people are equal.\nB: Yes, fundamentally.\nA: Fundamentally we all want the same thing.\nB: Belonging and respect.",funFact:"'Im' + 'Grunde' (ground/foundation). 'Im Grunde sind alle Menschen gleich' (Fundamentally, all people are equal). Looks at the foundation beneath the surface."},
{type:"teach",trg:"keineswegs",src:"by no means, not at all",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Keines' (none) + 'Wegs' (way). Stronger than 'nicht.'\nA formal negation used in academic and political discourse.",example:"A: Ist das akzeptabel?\nB: Keineswegs.\nA: Keineswegs bedeutet: auf gar keinen Fall.\nB: Eine starke Verneinung.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that acceptable?\nB: By no means.\nA: Keineswegs means: absolutely not.\nB: A strong negation.",funFact:"'Keines' (none) + 'Wegs' (way). 'Das ist keineswegs akzeptabel' (That is by no means acceptable). Stronger than 'nicht.' A formal negation."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"gleicherma\u00dfen",src:"equally, in equal measure"},{trg:"im Wesentlichen",src:"essentially, in essence"},{trg:"im Grunde",src:"fundamentally, basically"},{trg:"keineswegs",src:"by no means, not at all"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"keinesfalls",src:"under no circumstances",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Keines' (none) + 'Falls' (case). Even stronger than keineswegs.\nAn absolute rejection. Legal and formal register.",example:"A: Darf das passieren?\nB: Keinesfalls.\nA: Keinesfalls bedeutet: niemals.\nB: St\u00e4rker als keineswegs sogar.",exampleSrc:"A: May that happen?\nB: Under no circumstances.\nA: Keinesfalls means: never.\nB: Even stronger than keineswegs.",funFact:"'Keines' (none) + 'Falls' (case). 'Das darf keinesfalls passieren' (That must under no circumstances happen). Even stronger than keineswegs. An absolute rejection."},
{type:"fb",s:"Diskriminierung ist {1} akzeptabel.",a:["keineswegs"],opts:["keineswegs","gleichermaßen","letztlich","im Grunde"],hint:"A formal negation stronger than 'nicht.' Keines (none) + Wegs (way). By no means.",sSrc:"Discrimination is by no means acceptable."},
{type:"teach",trg:"letztlich",src:"ultimately, in the end",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"'Letzt' (last) + '-lich.' The concluding word in an argument.\nWhat remains when everything else is stripped away.",example:"A: Was z\u00e4hlt letztlich?\nB: Letztlich z\u00e4hlt nur der Respekt.\nA: Letztlich sind wir alle gleich.\nB: Ja, das ist die letztliche Wahrheit.",exampleSrc:"A: What ultimately counts?\nB: Ultimately, only respect counts.\nA: Ultimately we are all equal.\nB: Yes, that is the ultimate truth.",funFact:"'Letzt' (last) + '-lich.' The concluding word in an argument. 'Letztlich z\u00e4hlt nur der Respekt' (Ultimately, only respect counts). What remains when everything else is stripped away."},
{type:"tip",title:"Verweisw\u00f6rter: Pr\u00e4zises Verweisen",text:"German has a rich system of reference words (Verweiswörter) that create text cohesion.\n\ndieser/jener: this vs. that (near vs. far)\nsolcher/ein solcher: such (a type of)\nderjenige: the particular one (formal, with relative clause)\nderselbe: the identical one (not just similar)\nersterer/letzterer: the former/the latter (academic pair)\n\nAll decline like der-words. In writing, they replace repeated nouns and create elegant reference chains.\n'Die Wirtschaft und die Kultur: Erstere w\u00e4chst, letztere bl\u00fcht.'",deepDive:{title:"Double declension with derjenige/derselbe",text:"With derjenige and derselbe, BOTH parts decline:\n\nNominative: derjenige / diejenige / dasjenige\nAccusative: denjenigen / diejenige / dasjenige\nDative: demjenigen / derjenigen / demjenigen\nGenitive: desjenigen / derjenigen / desjenigen\n\nSame with derselbe:\nNominative: derselbe / dieselbe / dasselbe\nAccusative: denselben / dieselbe / dasselbe\nDative: demselben / derselben / demselben\n\nThe first part (der/die/das/den/dem/des) follows the article.\nThe second part (-jenige/-selbe) follows adjective declension."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Verweisw\u00f6rter: Deklinationsmuster",groups:[{label:"dieser/jener/solcher (wie der-W\u00f6rter)",rows:[{pronoun:"Nom m/f/n/pl",form:"dieser/diese/dieses/diese",src:"this (one)"},{pronoun:"Akk m/f/n/pl",form:"diesen/diese/dieses/diese",src:"this (one)"},{pronoun:"Dat m/f/n/pl",form:"diesem/dieser/diesem/diesen",src:"this (one)"},{pronoun:"Gen m/f/n/pl",form:"dieses/dieser/dieses/dieser",src:"of this (one)"}]},{label:"derjenige/derselbe (doppelte Deklination)",rows:[{pronoun:"Nom m/f/n",form:"derjenige/diejenige/dasjenige",src:"the (particular) one"},{pronoun:"Akk m/f/n",form:"denjenigen/diejenige/dasjenige",src:"the (particular) one"},{pronoun:"Dat m/f/n",form:"demjenigen/derjenigen/demjenigen",src:"the (particular) one"},{pronoun:"Gen m/f/n",form:"desjenigen/derjenigen/desjenigen",src:"of the (particular) one"}]}],note:"Dieser/jener/solcher: simple declension. Derjenige/derselbe: both parts decline."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Toleranz und Respekt sind wichtig. Ersterer ist passiv, letzterer aktiv.' Worauf beziehen sich ersterer/letzterer?",opts:["ersterer = Respekt, letzterer = Toleranz","beide beziehen sich auf Toleranz","ersterer = Toleranz, letzterer = Respekt","beide sind Adjektive"],ans:"ersterer = Toleranz, letzterer = Respekt",hint:"The first of a pair refers to whichever noun was named first in the previous sentence. The second refers to the second. Order matches order."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1}, der seine Herkunft leugnet, verliert einen Teil von sich.",a:["Derjenige"],opts:["Dieser","Jener","Derselbe","Derjenige"],hint:"A formal demonstrative that singles out a specific person and leads directly into a relative clause. More precise than 'dieser' or 'jener'.",sSrc:"The one who denies their heritage loses a part of themselves."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Wer offen ist, der gewinnt. Alles, was z\u00e4hlt, ist Respekt.' Beide S\u00e4tze verwenden...",opts:["Verweiswörter wie dieser/jener/derselbe","Kausalverbindungen","verallgemeinerte Relativs\u00e4tze","Fugenelemente in Komposita"],ans:"verallgemeinerte Relativs\u00e4tze",hint:"'Wer...' and 'alles, was...' are free relative patterns for universal statements."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} Mensch, der Vorurteile hat, sollte sich mit {2} auseinandersetzen.",blanks:{"1":"Derjenige","2":"diesen"},pool:["Derjenige","diesen","Dieser","jenen","Solcher","denen"],hint:"Formal demonstrative pronoun introducing a relative clause, plus an accusative plural form referring back to what was just mentioned.",sSrc:"The one who has prejudices should confront them."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"derselbe",src:"the same (identical)"},{trg:"derjenige",src:"the one who"},{trg:"ersterer",src:"the former"},{trg:"letzterer",src:"the latter"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'im Wesentlichen'?",opts:["essentially, in essence","the same one (neuter)","the same one (feminine)","the one which (neuter)"],ans:"essentially, in essence",hint:"im + Wesentlichen (the essential). Getting to the core of the matter."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1}.",a:["keinesfalls"],opts:["dieselbe","keinesfalls","dasselbe","dasjenige"],hint:"keines (none) + Falls (case). Under no circumstances, in no case whatsoever.",sSrc:"Under no circumstances."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l5",title:"Meinungsfreiheit",icon:"\u2696\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Meinungsfreiheit",desc:"Dinner table debate: equality, solidarity, and freedom of speech. Along the way, learn the Fugenelement system for compound nouns.",goals:["Learn the Fugenelement system for compound nouns","Debate integration, equality, and tolerance","Practice all three grammar constructs together"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Multikulturalitaet",src:"multiculturalism",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Multi + Kulturalitaet. The abstract concept.\nNo linking element between multi and Kulturalitaet.",example:"A: Multikulturalitaet ist eine Realitaet.\nB: Ja, besonders in Großstädte.\nA: Ist Multikulturalitaet immer positiv?\nB: Sie bringt Chancen und Herausforderungen.",exampleSrc:"A: Multiculturalism is a reality.\nB: Yes, especially in big cities.\nA: Is multiculturalism always positive?\nB: It brings opportunities and challenges.",funFact:"Multi + Kulturalitaet. The abstract concept. No Fugenelement between multi and Kulturalitaet. A political term debated intensely since the 1990s in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gleichberechtigung",src:"equal rights",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"COMPOUND: Gleich (equal) + Berechtigung (authorization).\nGleich (equal) + Berechtigung (authorization).\nArticle 3 of the Basic Law guarantees it.",example:"A: Gleichberechtigung steht im Grundgesetz.\nB: Seit 1949.\nA: Ist sie heute Realitaet?\nB: Auf dem Papier ja, im Alltag nicht immer.",exampleSrc:"A: Equal rights are in the constitution.\nB: Since 1949.\nA: Is it a reality today?\nB: On paper yes, in daily life not always.",funFact:"Gleich (equal) + Berechtigung (authorization). Article 3 of the Grundgesetz guarantees it. 'Gleichberechtigung von Mann und Frau' was added in 1949 against resistance."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Chancengleichheit",src:"equal opportunity",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Chancen + Gleichheit. The linking -n connects.\nThe ideal: everyone starts from the same position.",example:"A: Gibt es Chancengleichheit in Deutschland?\nB: Nicht für alle.\nA: Was fehlt?\nB: Bessere Bildung für alle Schichten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there equal opportunity in Germany?\nB: Not for everyone.\nA: What is missing?\nB: Better education for all social classes.",funFact:"Chancen (chances) + Gleichheit (equality). The Fugen-n connects the two parts. The ideal that everyone starts from the same position. Germany's three-track school system challenges this ideal."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was garantiert Artikel 3 des Grundgesetzes?",opts:["die Gleichberechtigung","die Chancengleichheit","die Meinungsfreiheit","die Multikulturalitaet"],ans:"Gleichberechtigung",hint:"Gleich (equal) + Berechtigung (authorization). A fundamental right since 1949."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Emanzipation",src:"emancipation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'emancipatio' (liberation).\nOriginally Roman law: a son becomes free.",example:"A: Emanzipation bedeutet Befreiung.\nB: Von welchen Zwang?\nA: Von jeder äußerlichen Bestimmung.\nB: Frauenemanzipation hat Deutschland verändert.",exampleSrc:"A: Emancipation means liberation.\nB: From what constraint?\nA: From any external determination.\nB: Women's emancipation changed Germany.",funFact:"In Roman law, 'emancipatio' meant freeing a son from his father's authority, literally 'releasing from the hand.' Frauenemanzipation has shaped German politics since the 1968 movement."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Solidaritaet",src:"solidarity",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French 'solidarite.' 'Solidaritaetszuschlag'\nwas Germany's tax for reunification.",example:"A: Solidaritaet ist wichtig.\nB: Besonders in Krisenzeiten.\nA: Was ist der Solidaritaetszuschlag?\nB: Eine Steuer für die Wiedervereinigung.",exampleSrc:"A: Solidarity is important.\nB: Especially in times of crisis.\nA: What is the solidarity surcharge?\nB: A tax for reunification.",funFact:"After reunification, Germany created the Solidaritaetszuschlag (solidarity surcharge), a tax where West Germans helped rebuild the East. Borrowed from French 'solidarite,' solidarity in action."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} war eine Steuer, die Deutschland nach der Wiedervereinigung einführte.",a:["Solidaritaet"],opts:["Emanzipation","Solidaritaet","Gleichberechtigung","Zivilgesellschaft"],hint:"The French-derived word for standing together. Its German compound form funded the reunification of East and West.",sSrc:"Solidarity was a tax that Germany introduced after reunification."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zivilgesellschaft",src:"civil society",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zivil + Gesellschaft. Everything between state and individual.\nGermany's 600,000 clubs are the backbone.",example:"A: Was ist Zivilgesellschaft?\nB: Vereine, Initiativen, Organisationen.\nA: Warum ist sie wichtig?\nB: Sie fuellt die Luecke zwischen Staat und Bürger.",exampleSrc:"A: What is civil society?\nB: Clubs, initiatives, organizations.\nA: Why is it important?\nB: It fills the gap between state and citizen.",funFact:"Zivil (civil) + Gesellschaft (society). Organizations, clubs, initiatives: everything between state and individual. Germany's 600,000 Vereine are the backbone of the Zivilgesellschaft."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was sind Beispiele für die Zivilgesellschaft?",opts:["die Bundesregierung und das Parlament","die Armee und die Polizei","Vereine, Initiativen und Organisationen","die Börse und die Banken"],ans:"Vereine, Initiativen und Organisationen",hint:"The space between the state and the individual: clubs, grassroots groups, and non-governmental organisations."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ausgrenzung",src:"exclusion, marginalization",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Aus (out) + Grenzung (bordering). To draw a line\nand leave someone outside. Opposite of inclusion.",example:"A: Ausgrenzung ist ein gesellschaftliches Problem.\nB: Ja, sie trifft viele Gruppen.\nA: Wie kann man Ausgrenzung bekaempfen?\nB: Durch Inklusion und offenen Dialog.",exampleSrc:"A: Exclusion is a societal problem.\nB: Yes, it affects many groups.\nA: How can you fight exclusion?\nB: Through inclusion and open dialogue.",funFact:"Aus (out) + Grenzung (bordering). Drawing a border around someone and pushing them out. 'Soziale Ausgrenzung' (social exclusion) is the opposite of Inklusion."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fremdenfeindlichkeit",src:"xenophobia",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Fremden (foreigners) + Feindlichkeit (hostility).\nA compound that names the problem precisely.",example:"A: Fremdenfeindlichkeit existiert leider noch.\nB: In vielen Ländern.\nA: Wie bekaempft man sie?\nB: Durch Bildung und Begegnung.",exampleSrc:"A: Xenophobia unfortunately still exists.\nB: In many countries.\nA: How do you fight it?\nB: Through education and encounter.",funFact:"Fremden (foreigners) + Feindlichkeit (hostility). A compound that names the problem precisely. Germans discuss Fremdenfeindlichkeit openly as a societal challenge."},
{type:"fb",s:"Soziale {1} ist das Gegenteil von Inklusion.",a:["Ausgrenzung"],opts:["Akzeptanz","Chancengleichheit","Emanzipation","Ausgrenzung"],hint:"Aus (out) + Grenzung (bordering). Drawing a border and pushing someone outside it.",sSrc:"Social exclusion is the opposite of inclusion."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Akzeptanz",src:"acceptance",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'acceptare.' Stronger than tolerance:\ntolerate = endure, accept = embrace.",example:"A: Akzeptanz ist mehr als Toleranz.\nB: Was ist der Unterschied?\nA: Tolerieren heißt ertragen. Akzeptieren heißt annehmen.\nB: Gesellschaftliche Akzeptanz ist das Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: Acceptance is more than tolerance.\nB: What is the difference?\nA: To tolerate means to endure. To accept means to embrace.\nB: Societal acceptance is the goal.",funFact:"Akzeptanz is stronger than Toleranz. Tolerating means merely enduring, while accepting means genuinely embracing. 'Gesellschaftliche Akzeptanz' (societal acceptance) is the next step beyond tolerance. Latin root: 'acceptare.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist stärker: Toleranz oder Akzeptanz?",opts:["Akzeptanz, weil Annehmen stärker als Ertragen ist","Toleranz, weil Ertragen aktiver als Annehmen ist","beide Begriffe sind vollkommen identisch","keine von beiden hat eine wirklich klare Bedeutung"],ans:"Akzeptanz, weil Annehmen stärker als Ertragen ist",hint:"Tolerating means enduring. Accepting means embracing. One goes further than the other."},
{type:"fb",s:"Chancen + {1} = das Kompositum fuer 'equal opportunity'.",a:["gleichheit"],opts:["berechtigung","gleichheit","freiheit","ordnung"],hint:"The second component of this compound means 'sameness' or 'equality.' Not 'authorization' or 'freedom.'",sSrc:"Chances + equality = equal opportunity."},
{type:"mc",q:"Multikulturalitaet bezeichnet...",opts:["eine einzelne klar dominante Kultur","die ausdrückliche Ablehnung fremder Kulturen","das abstrakte Konzept einer Gesellschaft mit vielen Kulturen","die vollständige Gleichheit aller Religionen"],ans:"das abstrakte Konzept einer Gesellschaft mit vielen Kulturen",hint:"Multi (many) + Kulturalitaet. The abstract concept. Not a single culture, but many existing together."}
]},

// --- Lesson: Fuer Gleichberechtigung ---
{id:"deu_r32l6",title:"Fuer Gleichberechtigung",icon:"✊",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Fuer Gleichberechtigung",desc:"Action verbs for social change: discriminate, exclude, emancipate, overcome. Plus adjectives for describing an enlightened, equal society.",goals:["Learn verbs of social action","Use adjectives for social values","Discuss equality and inclusion"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufgeklaert",src:"enlightened",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Auf (up) + geklaert (cleared). From the Enlightenment.\nKant's definition: the courage to use one's own reason.",example:"A: Eine aufgeklaerte Gesellschaft denkt kritisch.\nB: Ja, das ist das Erbe der Aufklaerung.\nA: Sind wir heute aufgeklaert genug?\nB: Es gibt immer Raum für mehr Aufklaerung.",exampleSrc:"A: An enlightened society thinks critically.\nB: Yes, that is the legacy of the Enlightenment.\nA: Are we enlightened enough today?\nB: There is always room for more enlightenment.",funFact:"Kant defined Aufklaerung as 'the courage to use your own understanding.' The past participle aufgeklaert became an adjective meaning enlightened. An aufgeklaerter Mensch questions everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gleichberechtigt",src:"having equal rights",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Gleich (equal) + berechtigt (authorized).\nThe adjective form of Gleichberechtigung.",example:"A: Maenner und Frauen sind gleichberechtigt.\nB: So steht es im Gesetz.\nA: Gleichberechtigte Partner teilen alles.\nB: Theorie und Praxis stimmen nicht immer überein.",exampleSrc:"A: Men and women have equal rights.\nB: So it says in the law.\nA: Equal partners share everything.\nB: Theory and practice don't always match.",funFact:"Gleich (equal) + berechtigt (authorized). The adjective form of Gleichberechtigung. Two things standing on the same legal ground."},
{type:"teach",trg:"solidarisch",src:"showing solidarity",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Solidar + -isch. 'Sich solidarisch erklären'\nis a strong political statement in Germany.",example:"A: Wir müssen solidarisch handeln.\nB: Was bedeutet das konkret?\nA: Fuereinander einstehen.\nB: Sich solidarisch erklären ist der erste Schritt.",exampleSrc:"A: We must act in solidarity.\nB: What does that mean concretely?\nA: Standing up for each other.\nB: Declaring solidarity is the first step.",funFact:"Solidar + -isch. 'Sich solidarisch erklären' (to declare solidarity) is a powerful political statement in Germany. The adjective form of Solidaritaet."},
{type:"teach",trg:"unvoreingenommen",src:"unprejudiced, unbiased",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Un- (not) + voreingenommen (biased).\nSeven syllables against prejudice.",example:"A: Richter müssen unvoreingenommen urteilen.\nB: Das ist die Theorie.\nA: Kann man wirklich unvoreingenommen sein?\nB: Man kann es versuchen.",exampleSrc:"A: Judges must judge without bias.\nB: That is the theory.\nA: Can one really be unbiased?\nB: One can try.",funFact:"Un- (not) + voreingenommen (prejudiced). A seven-syllable antonym of voreingenommen. The negative prefix un- reverses the prejudice. Easier said than practiced."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zeitgemaess",src:"contemporary, up to date",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Zeit (time) + gemaess (according to). What fits\nthe current era. Values that evolve.",example:"A: Sind diese Werte noch zeitgemaess?\nB: Manche ja, manche nein.\nA: Was ist nicht mehr zeitgemaess?\nB: Starre Rollenbilder zum Beispiel.",exampleSrc:"A: Are these values still contemporary?\nB: Some yes, some no.\nA: What is no longer contemporary?\nB: Rigid role models for example.",funFact:"Zeit (time) + gemaess (according to). According to the current time. Values that evolve as society changes. What fits the era. The opposite: unzeitgemaess."},
{type:"mc",q:"Richter sollen ohne Vorurteile urteilen. Sie sollen ... sein.",opts:["unvoreingenommen","zeitgemaess","solidarisch","gleichberechtigt"],ans:"unvoreingenommen",hint:"Un- + voreingenommen. Seven syllables against prejudice. The negative prefix reverses the bias."},

{type:"teach",trg:"diskriminieren",src:"to discriminate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'discriminare.' Inseparable.\n'Niemand darf diskriminiert werden' (Anti-Discrimination Act).",example:"A: Niemand darf diskriminiert werden.\nB: Das steht im Gesetz.\nA: Trotzdem wird diskriminiert.\nB: Deshalb brauchen wir das Gesetz.",exampleSrc:"A: Nobody may be discriminated against.\nB: It says so in the law.\nA: Yet discrimination happens.\nB: That is why we need the law.",funFact:"Germany's AGG (Allgemeines Gleichbehandlungsgesetz) makes the prohibition of discrimination legally enforceable. The Latin root 'discriminare' originally just meant to distinguish between things."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausgrenzen",src:"to exclude, to marginalize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Aus (out) + grenzen (to border). Separable:\n'Sie grenzen ihn aus.' To leave someone outside.",example:"A: Man sollte niemanden ausgrenzen.\nB: Stimmt, aber es passiert oft.\nA: Warum grenzen Menschen andere aus?\nB: Aus Angst vor dem Unbekannten.",exampleSrc:"A: One should not exclude anyone.\nB: True, but it happens often.\nA: Why do people exclude others?\nB: Out of fear of the unknown.",funFact:"Aus (out) + grenzen (to border). Separable: 'Sie grenzen ihn aus.' Drawing a line and placing someone outside it. The opposite of einschliessen (to include)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"emanzipieren",src:"to emancipate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'emancipare.' Reflexive: 'sich emanzipieren.'\nInseparable. The path from dependence to freedom.",example:"A: Frauen mussten sich emanzipieren.\nB: Ein langer Kampf.\nA: Kann man sich von Vorurteilen emanzipieren?\nB: Ja, durch Reflexion und Mut.",exampleSrc:"A: Women had to emancipate themselves.\nB: A long struggle.\nA: Can one emancipate oneself from prejudices?\nB: Yes, through reflection and courage.",funFact:"As a reflexive verb, 'sich emanzipieren' captures the journey from dependence to independence. Latin 'emancipare' originally meant releasing someone from another's authority."},
{type:"fb",s:"Niemand darf aufgrund seiner Herkunft {1} werden.",a:["diskriminiert"],opts:["emanzipiert","diskriminiert","ausgegrenzt","solidarisiert"],hint:"From Latin 'discriminare.' The AGG makes this a legal prohibition. Non-separable -ieren verb.",sSrc:"Nobody may be discriminated against because of their origin."},

{type:"teach",trg:"überwinden",src:"to overcome",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Über (over) + winden (to wind/struggle). Strong:\nüberwand/überwunden. Inseparable.",example:"A: Wir müssen Vorurteile überwinden.\nB: Das ist leichter gesagt als getan.\nA: Hat Yilmaz Barrieren überwunden?\nB: Ja, viele. Und sie überwand sie mit Geduld.",exampleSrc:"A: We must overcome prejudices.\nB: That is easier said than done.\nA: Did Yilmaz overcome barriers?\nB: Yes, many. And she overcame them with patience.",funFact:"Über (over) + winden (to wind/struggle). Strong verb: überwinden/überwand/überwunden. Not separable. Struggling over an obstacle until you are past it."},
{type:"tip",title:"Fugenelemente: Der Kleber deutscher Komposita",text:"German compound nouns need connecting elements (Fugenelemente) between their parts. The most important:\n\nFugen-s: Meinungsfreiheit, Identitaetskrise, Lebensqualitaet. Most common after -ung, -heit, -keit, -tion, -taet, -schaft.\nFugen-n: Chancengleichheit, Generationenkonflikt. After feminine nouns ending in -e.\nFugen-en: Frauenemanzipation, Menschenwürde. After plural or weak nouns.\nFugen-er: Kinderfreundlich, Bilderbuch. After some neuter nouns.\nNo Fugenelement: Weltanschauung, Schulkind. Sometimes nothing is needed.\n\nThe Fugenelement does NOT indicate genitive or plural. It is purely phonetic glue.",deepDive:{title:"Fugenelemente: formation and patterns",text:"The Fugenelement does NOT indicate genitive or plural. It is purely phonetic glue that makes compounds easier to pronounce.\n\nRules of thumb:\n-ung always takes Fugen-s: Meinungsfreiheit, Ordnungssystem\n-heit/-keit always takes Fugen-s: Freiheitskampf, Moeglichkeitsform\n-tion/-taet always takes Fugen-s: Identitaetskrise, Kommunikationsproblem\n-schaft always takes Fugen-s: Gesellschaftskritik, Wissenschaftsrat\n\nFeminine nouns ending in -e often take Fugen-n: Chancengleichheit, Sonnenschein\nWeak/plural nouns take Fugen-en: Menschenwürde, Frauenemanzipation\n\nThere are exceptions, but these patterns cover 90% of cases."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Fugenelemente in gaengigen Komposita",groups:[{label:"Fugen-s (am häufigsten)",rows:[{pronoun:"nach -ung",form:"Meinungsfreiheit",src:"freedom of opinion"},{pronoun:"nach -heit/-keit",form:"Freiheitskampf",src:"freedom struggle"},{pronoun:"nach -tion/-taet",form:"Identitaetskrise",src:"identity crisis"},{pronoun:"nach -schaft",form:"Gesellschaftskritik",src:"social criticism"}]},{label:"Fugen-n/-en (feminine -e, schwache Substantive)",rows:[{pronoun:"Fugen-n",form:"Chancengleichheit",src:"equal opportunity"},{pronoun:"Fugen-en",form:"Menschenwürde",src:"human dignity"},{pronoun:"Fugen-en",form:"Frauenemanzipation",src:"women's emancipation"}]},{label:"Kein Fugenelement",rows:[{pronoun:"null",form:"Weltanschauung",src:"worldview"},{pronoun:"null",form:"Schulkind",src:"schoolchild"}]}],note:"The linking element is not genitive and not plural. It is purely phonetic glue."},
{type:"mc",q:"Im Wort Meinungsfreiheit ist das -s- zwischen Meinung und Freiheit...",opts:["ein Genitivmarker nach -ung (Genitivattribut)","eine Pluralendung","ein Fugenelement (Verbindungselement)","ein Teil des Wortstamms"],ans:"ein Fugenelement (Verbindungselement)",hint:"Not genitive, not plural. Pure phonetic glue. Words ending in -ung almost always take Fugen-s."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Fugenelement nach Nomen auf -taet lautet: Identität + {1} + ...",a:["s"],opts:["n","en","s"],hint:"Check the verb_table: which linking element follows words ending in -tion or -taet?",sSrc:"The Fugenelement after nouns ending in -taet is: s"},
{type:"mc",q:"Mia sagt: 'Diejenigen, die Gleichberechtigung fordern, müssen kaempfen.' Yilmaz sagt: 'Wer zwischen zwei Kulturen lebt, der erlebt beides.' Welche Konstrukte erscheinen hier?",opts:["Verweiswort (diejenigen) + verallgemeinernder Relativsatz (wer...der)","nur Verweiswörter ohne Relativsatz wie derjenige/derselbe/dieser wie derjenige/derselbe/dieser wie derjenige/derselbe/dieser","nur einfache Relativsaetze","nur Fugenelemente in Komposita"],ans:"Verweiswort (diejenigen) + verallgemeinernder Relativsatz (wer...der)",hint:"Both sentences use structures that refer to people in a general way. One uses a formal demonstrative plus a relative clause. The other uses a universal relative opener paired with a resumptive pronoun."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} Menschen, die diskriminiert werden, brauchen gesellschaftliche {2}.",blanks:{"1":"Diejenigen","2":"Akzeptanz"},pool:["Diejenigen","Akzeptanz","Solche","Toleranz","Diese","Solidaritaet"],hint:"The formal demonstrative for 'those who' plus a noun meaning acceptance.",sSrc:"Those (specific ones) who are discriminated against need societal acceptance."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Gleichberechtigung",src:"equal rights"},{trg:"Ausgrenzung",src:"exclusion"},{trg:"Fremdenfeindlichkeit",src:"xenophobia"},{trg:"Emanzipation",src:"emancipation"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'ausgrenzen'?",opts:["to emancipate and liberate","to exclude, to marginalize","to discriminate","to overcome"],ans:"to exclude, to marginalize",hint:"Aus (out) + grenzen (to border). Drawing a line and placing someone outside it. Separable verb."},
{type:"fb",s:"Eine {1}e Gesellschaft akzeptiert Vielfalt und setzt auf Vernunft.",a:["aufgeklaert"],opts:["aufgeklaert","ausgegrenzt","emanzipiert","diskriminiert"],hint:"A society guided by reason and education. Related to the Enlightenment (die Aufklaerung).",sSrc:"An enlightened society accepts diversity and relies on reason."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l7",title:"Was wirklich zaehlt",icon:"\uD83C\uDF03",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Was wirklich zaehlt",desc:"Night walk through Berlin. Verumius reflects on identity, culture, and belonging. All three grammar constructs in complex combinations.",goals:["Practice all three grammar constructs in complex combinations","Master advanced identity and culture vocabulary","Build coherent argumentative texts"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Diversitaet",src:"diversity (formal/academic)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'diversitas' (difference).\nMore formal than Vielfalt. Corporate terminology.",example:"A: Diversitaet ist ein Unternehmensziel.\nB: Was bedeutet das konkret?\nA: Vielfalt in Teams und Fuehrungspositionen.\nB: Diversitaetsmanagement ist eine eigene Abteilung.",exampleSrc:"A: Diversity is a corporate goal.\nB: What does that mean concretely?\nA: Variety in teams and leadership positions.\nB: Diversity management is its own department.",funFact:"Many German companies now have a Diversitaetsmanagement department. The word is more formal than its native synonym Vielfalt and entered German politics in the 2000s. Latin root: 'diversitas' (difference)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Assimilation",src:"assimilation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'assimilare' (to make similar).\nAssimilation erases differences, integration preserves them.",example:"A: Ist Assimilation noetig?\nB: Das wird kontrovers diskutiert.\nA: Was ist der Unterschied zur Integration?\nB: Assimilation loescht Unterschiede. Integration bewahrt sie.",exampleSrc:"A: Is assimilation necessary?\nB: That is controversially debated.\nA: What is the difference from integration?\nB: Assimilation erases differences. Integration preserves them.",funFact:"Germans draw a sharp distinction: Assimilation erases cultural differences, while Integration preserves them. The Latin root 'assimilare' literally meant to make similar."},
{type:"mc",q:"Assimilation und Integration: Was ist der Hauptunterschied?",opts:["Assimilation loescht Unterschiede, Integration bewahrt sie","beide Begriffe sind Synonyme","Integration ist formeller als Assimilation","Assimilation bewahrt Unterschiede, Integration loescht sie"],ans:"Assimilation loescht Unterschiede, Integration bewahrt sie",hint:"One process dissolves original identity into the dominant culture. The other preserves both."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Interkulturalitaet",src:"interculturality",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Inter (between) + Kulturalitaet. Cultures that\nmutually influence each other. Stronger than multicultural.",example:"A: Interkulturalitaet geht über Multikulti hinaus.\nB: Wie?\nA: Es geht um aktiven Austausch zwischen Kulturen.\nB: Nicht nur nebeneinander, sondern miteinander.",exampleSrc:"A: Interculturality goes beyond multiculturalism.\nB: How?\nA: It is about active exchange between cultures.\nB: Not just side by side, but with each other.",funFact:"Inter (between) + Kulturalitaet. The academic concept of cultures interacting and influencing each other. Stronger than multikulturell: not just coexisting but actively exchanging."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Leitkultur",src:"guiding culture, dominant culture",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Leit (leading) + Kultur. A controversial political\nterm. Has divided left and right since 2000.",example:"A: Was ist Leitkultur?\nB: Eine umstrittene Idee.\nA: Soll es eine Leitkultur geben?\nB: Darüber streiten sich Politiker seit Jahrzehnten.",exampleSrc:"A: What is Leitkultur?\nB: A controversial idea.\nA: Should there be a guiding culture?\nB: Politicians have been arguing about that for decades.",funFact:"Leit (guiding) + Kultur. A controversial German political term. Does Germany have a Leitkultur that immigrants should adopt? The debate divides left and right since 2000."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Minderheitenschutz",src:"minority protection",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Minderheiten + Schutz. Linking -en connects.\nGermany protects four national minorities.",example:"A: Minderheitenschutz ist ein Grundrecht.\nB: Welche Minderheiten sind geschützt?\nA: Daenen, Friesen, Sorben und Sinti/Roma.\nB: Das steht im Grundgesetz.",exampleSrc:"A: Minority protection is a fundamental right.\nB: Which minorities are protected?\nA: Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Sinti/Roma.\nB: It is in the constitution.",funFact:"Minderheiten (minorities) + Schutz (protection). The Fugen-en connects them. Germany officially protects four national minorities: Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Sinti/Roma."},
{type:"fb",s:"Deutschland schützt vier nationale Minderheiten: Dänen, Friesen, Sorben und Sinti/Roma. Das ist {1}.",a:["Minderheitenschutz"],opts:["Leitkultur","Minderheitenschutz","Assimilation","Interkulturalitaet"],hint:"Minderheiten (minorities) + Schutz (protection). A constitutional principle for protecting smaller groups.",sSrc:"Germany protects four national minorities. That is minority protection."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Subkultur",src:"subculture",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Sub (under) + Kultur. Berlin is Germany's\nsubculture capital: punk, techno, street art.",example:"A: Berlin hat eine lebendige Subkultur.\nB: Welche zum Beispiel?\nA: Techno, Street Art, alternative Szenen.\nB: Kreuzberg allein hat Dutzende.",exampleSrc:"A: Berlin has a vibrant subculture.\nB: Which ones for example?\nA: Techno, street art, alternative scenes.\nB: Kreuzberg alone has dozens.",funFact:"Sub (under) + Kultur. Berlin is Germany's subculture capital: punk, techno, street art, squatter movements. Kreuzberg alone hosts dozens of distinct Subkulturen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Kulturgut",src:"cultural asset, cultural heritage",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Kultur + Gut (good/asset). 'Immaterielles Kulturgut'\nis UNESCO-protected. German bread is included.",example:"A: Deutsches Brot ist Kulturgut.\nB: Von der UNESCO anerkannt?\nA: Ja, immaterielles Kulturgut.\nB: Über 3.000 Brotsorten!",exampleSrc:"A: German bread is cultural heritage.\nB: Recognized by UNESCO?\nA: Yes, intangible cultural heritage.\nB: Over 3,000 types of bread!",funFact:"Kultur + Gut (good/asset). 'Immaterielles Kulturgut' (intangible cultural heritage): German bread culture, carnival, Schrebergaerten. UNESCO recognizes many German Kulturgueter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Werteordnung",src:"value system, moral order",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Werte (values) + Ordnung (order). The structured\nhierarchy of societal values.",example:"A: Jede Gesellschaft hat eine Werteordnung.\nB: Wer bestimmt sie?\nA: Das Grundgesetz legt die Basis.\nB: Menschenwürde steht an erster Stelle.",exampleSrc:"A: Every society has a value system.\nB: Who determines it?\nA: The constitution sets the foundation.\nB: Human dignity comes first.",funFact:"Werte (values) + Ordnung (order). The structured hierarchy of a society's values. The Grundgesetz establishes Germany's official Werteordnung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zukunftsvision",src:"future vision",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zukunft + s (linking -s) + Vision. The linking -s\nconnects Zukunft with Vision.",example:"A: Haben wir eine gemeinsame Zukunftsvision?\nB: Das ist die grosse Frage.\nA: Politisch streiten wir darüber.\nB: Aber eine Vision brauchen wir.",exampleSrc:"A: Do we have a shared future vision?\nB: That is the big question.\nA: Politically we argue about it.\nB: But we need a vision.",funFact:"Zukunft (future) + s (Fugen-s) + Vision. The Fugen-s links Zukunft to Vision. 'Eine gemeinsame Zukunftsvision' is what political leaders call for."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Umbruch",src:"upheaval, radical change",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Um (around) + Bruch (break). Stronger than Wandel:\nUmbruch implies rupture and rebuilding.",example:"A: Die Wiedervereinigung war ein Umbruch.\nB: Ja, alles änderte sich.\nA: Gibt es heute einen Umbruch?\nB: Die Digitalisierung ist einer.",exampleSrc:"A: Reunification was an upheaval.\nB: Yes, everything changed.\nA: Is there an upheaval today?\nB: Digitalization is one.",funFact:"Um (around/over) + Bruch (break). Stronger than Wandel: Umbruch implies breaking and rebuilding. German reunification was an Umbruch. The word carries the weight of systemic change."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Wiedervereinigung 1990 war ein gesellschaftlicher...",opts:["Wandel","Aufschwung","Umbruch","Konflikt"],ans:"Umbruch",hint:"Um (around) + Bruch (break). Stronger than Wandel: implies breaking and rebuilding. Systemic change."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l7b",title:"Was wirklich zaehlt (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF03",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Was wirklich zaehlt (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gesinnung",src:"mindset, political disposition",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'sinnen' (to ponder). 'Gesinnungsprüfung'\nwas conducted during the Nazi and GDR eras.",example:"A: Gesinnung ist eine politische Haltung.\nB: Darf man nach Gesinnung fragen?\nA: In einer Demokratie: nein.\nB: Gesinnungsprüfungen sind verboten.",exampleSrc:"A: Gesinnung is a political attitude.\nB: May one ask about someone's Gesinnung?\nA: In a democracy: no.\nB: Ideological screenings are prohibited.",funFact:"Gesinnungspruefung (ideological screening) was used during both the Nazi and DDR eras. The root verb 'sinnen' means to ponder, but the noun Gesinnung carries heavy historical weight in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Rollenverteilung",src:"role distribution",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Rollen + Verteilung. How roles are distributed\nin society: gender, family, profession.",example:"A: Die traditionelle Rollenverteilung ändert sich.\nB: Langsam, aber stetig.\nA: Wer bestimmt die Rollenverteilung?\nB: Gesellschaft, Kultur und jeder Einzelne.",exampleSrc:"A: The traditional role distribution is changing.\nB: Slowly but steadily.\nA: Who determines the role distribution?\nB: Society, culture, and each individual.",funFact:"Rollen (roles) + Verteilung (distribution). How roles are assigned in society: gender roles, family roles, professional roles. 'Traditionelle Rollenverteilung' is being renegotiated."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Moral",src:"morals, morality",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'moralis.' Double meaning: ethical\nprinciples AND collective morale ('die Moral sinkt').",example:"A: Was ist die Moral der Geschichte?\nB: Dass Toleranz wichtig ist.\nA: Moral hat zwei Bedeutungen.\nB: Ja: Ethik und Stimmung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the moral of the story?\nB: That tolerance is important.\nA: Moral has two meanings.\nB: Yes: ethics and morale.",funFact:"Did you know Moral has two meanings in German? 'Die Moral der Geschichte' means the moral of the story, but 'Die Moral sinkt' means morale is dropping. Latin root: 'moralis' (relating to customs)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"fremdbestimmt",src:"externally determined",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Fremd (foreign/external) + bestimmt (determined).\nOpposite of self-determined. Core concept in freedom philosophy.",example:"A: Ein fremdbestimmtes Leben ist kein freies Leben.\nB: Was ist das Gegenteil?\nA: Selbstbestimmt.\nB: Jeder sollte selbstbestimmt leben können.",exampleSrc:"A: An externally determined life is not a free life.\nB: What is the opposite?\nA: Self-determined.\nB: Everyone should be able to live self-determined.",funFact:"Fremd (foreign/external) + bestimmt (determined). The opposite of selbstbestimmt (self-determined). A key concept in German philosophy of freedom."},
{type:"teach",trg:"rassistisch",src:"racist",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Rasse + -istisch. German discourse uses the\nword directly and without euphemism.",example:"A: Rassistische Diskriminierung ist verboten.\nB: Steht das im Gesetz?\nA: Ja, im AGG.\nB: Das Allgemeine Gleichbehandlungsgesetz.",exampleSrc:"A: Racial discrimination is prohibited.\nB: Is that in the law?\nA: Yes, in the AGG.\nB: The General Equal Treatment Act.",funFact:"Rasse (race) + -istisch. German discourse uses the word directly and without euphemism. The AGG explicitly prohibits rassistische Benachteiligung."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Rollenverteilung",src:"role distribution"},{trg:"die Moral",src:"morals, morality"},{trg:"fremdbestimmt",src:"externally determined"},{trg:"rassistisch",src:"racist"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"stereotyp",src:"stereotypical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'stereos' (solid) + 'typos' (impression).\nAlso a noun: 'ein Stereotyp' (das, neuter).",example:"A: Stereotype Vorstellungen sind gefaehrlich.\nB: Warum?\nA: Sie vereinfachen die Realitaet.\nB: Und sie widerstehen Veraenderung.",exampleSrc:"A: Stereotypical ideas are dangerous.\nB: Why?\nA: They simplify reality.\nB: And they resist change.",funFact:"The Greek roots 'stereos' (solid) + 'typos' (impression) reveal why stereotypes are so stubborn: they are literally solid impressions that resist change. Works as both adjective and noun in German."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ein {1} Leben ist das Gegenteil von Selbstbestimmung.",a:["fremdbestimmtes"],opts:["rassistisches","stereotypes","zeitgemaesses","fremdbestimmtes"],hint:"Fremd (external) + bestimmt (determined). When someone else makes the decisions about your life.",sSrc:"An externally determined life is the opposite of self-determination."},
{type:"teach",trg:"tolerieren",src:"to tolerate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'tolerare' (to endure). More passive\nthan accepting: one endures rather than embraces.",example:"A: Soll man alles tolerieren?\nB: Nein, es gibt Grenzen.\nA: Tolerieren ist passiver als akzeptieren.\nB: Richtig. Tolerieren heißt ertragen.",exampleSrc:"A: Should one tolerate everything?\nB: No, there are limits.\nA: Tolerating is more passive than accepting.\nB: Right. To tolerate means to endure.",funFact:"Tolerieren is more passive than akzeptieren: you merely endure rather than embrace. The Latin root 'tolerare' literally meant to bear a burden. 'Unterschiede tolerieren' is the minimum, not the goal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verdraengen",src:"to suppress, to repress",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + draengen (to push). Inseparable.\nFreud's Verdraengung is a cornerstone of psychoanalysis.",example:"A: Menschen verdraengen unangenehme Erinnerungen.\nB: Ist das gesund?\nA: Kurzfristig vielleicht. Langfristig nein.\nB: Verdraengung führt zu Problemen.",exampleSrc:"A: People suppress unpleasant memories.\nB: Is that healthy?\nA: In the short term perhaps. Long term no.\nB: Repression leads to problems.",funFact:"Ver- + draengen (to push). Not separable. Pushing something away so it disappears from view. Freud's Verdraengung (repression) is a cornerstone of psychoanalysis."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius denkt: 'Alles, was ich erlebt habe, hat meine Identitaet verändert. Wer zwischen Kulturen lebt, der gehört zu beiden. Dasselbe Gefühl kennt Yilmaz.' Welche drei Konstrukte erscheinen?",opts:["Relativsatz + Verweiswort","nur Verweiswörter im Text","nur Relativsaetze ohne Verweis","Fugenelemente in Komposita"],ans:"Relativsatz + Verweiswort",hint:"'Wer... der' and 'alles, was...' are generalizing relative clauses. 'Dasselbe' is a demonstrative reference word."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Fugenelement nach Nomen auf -heit/-keit/-schaft lautet: Zukunft + {1} + ...",a:["s"],opts:["n","s","en"],hint:"Nouns ending in -heit, -keit, or -schaft all follow the same pattern. Which linking element do they take?",sSrc:"The Fugenelement after nouns ending in -heit/-keit/-schaft is: s"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Toleranz und Akzeptanz sind verwandt. Erstere ist passiv, letztere aktiv.' Erstere bezieht sich auf...",opts:["beide","Akzeptanz (die zweit Genannte)","Toleranz (die zuerst Genannte)","keines von beiden"],ans:"Toleranz (die zuerst Genannte)",hint:"'Erstere' = the first mentioned, the first of the two terms named."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1}, was zaehlt, ist nicht {2} Meinung, sondern die Bereitschaft, andere zu verstehen.",blanks:{"1":"Alles","2":"dieselbe"},pool:["Alles","dieselbe","Was","die gleiche","Das","derselbe"],hint:"Two structures: a free relative clause for universal statements plus a demonstrative adjective expressing sameness. Neither sameness nor uniformity is what counts.",sSrc:"Everything that counts is not the same opinion, but the willingness to understand others."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Leitkultur",src:"guiding/dominant culture"},{trg:"Assimilation",src:"cultural absorption"},{trg:"Minderheitenschutz",src:"minority protection"},{trg:"Umbruch",src:"upheaval"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Gesinnung'?",opts:["assimilation","cultural asset, cultural heritage","mindset, political disposition","diversity (formal/academic)"],ans:"mindset, political disposition",hint:"From gesinnt (disposed). Your deep ideological or moral convictions, not just surface opinions."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wer bestimmt {1}?",a:["die Rollenverteilung"],opts:["die Diversitaet","stereotyp","die Leitkultur","die Rollenverteilung"],hint:"Rolle (role) + Verteilung (distribution). How roles are assigned in a group or society.",sSrc:"Who determines the role distribution?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Moral'?",opts:["to suppress, to repress","to tolerate","cultural asset, cultural heritage","morals, morality"],ans:"morals, morality",hint:"A Latin loan (moralis). The shared sense of right and wrong in a society."},
{type:"fb",s:"Soll man alles {1}?",a:["tolerieren"],opts:["tolerieren","die Subkultur","der Minderheitenschutz","fremdbestimmt"],hint:"Latin loan: tolerare (to endure). To accept something you may not agree with.",sSrc:"Should one tolerate everything?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'verdraengen'?",opts:["to suppress, to repress","subculture","future vision","role distribution"],ans:"to suppress, to repress",hint:"ver- + drängen (to push). To push something out of consciousness or out of a space."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l8",title:"Die grosse Debatte",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die grosse Debatte",desc:"Prove your mastery of identity and culture vocabulary. Test all three grammar constructs. Show you can build coherent arguments about society.",goals:["Test all three grammar constructs","Prove mastery of identity vocabulary","Build coherent arguments about society"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Abstammung",src:"descent, lineage",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ab (from) + Stammung (descent). Where your\nfamily tree grows from. Contains 'Stamm' (trunk/tribe).",example:"A: Die Abstammung spielt in vielen Kulturen eine Rolle.\nB: In Deutschland auch?\nA: Weniger als früher.\nB: Heute zaehlt mehr, was man tut.",exampleSrc:"A: Descent plays a role in many cultures.\nB: In Germany too?\nA: Less than before.\nB: Today what you do matters more.",funFact:"Ab (from) + Stammung (stemming). Where your family tree grows from. The word contains 'Stamm' (trunk/tribe): you descend from a trunk. 'Ethnische Abstammung' (ethnic descent)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Individualismus",src:"individualism",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Individual + -ismus. The Western value of the individual.\nGermany balances individualism and community.",example:"A: Individualismus ist ein westlicher Wert.\nB: Steht er im Konflikt mit Gemeinschaft?\nA: Manchmal.\nB: Deutschland versucht, beides zu vereinen.",exampleSrc:"A: Individualism is a Western value.\nB: Does it conflict with community?\nA: Sometimes.\nB: Germany tries to combine both.",funFact:"Individual + -ismus. The Western value of the individual over the collective. Germany balances Individualismus with Gemeinschaft (community). The -ismus suffix always creates masculine nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kompetenz",src:"competence, skill",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'competentia.' 'Interkulturelle Kompetenz'\nis a formal qualification in the job market.",example:"A: Interkulturelle Kompetenz ist gefragt.\nB: Was bedeutet das?\nA: Die Faehigkeit, mit verschiedenen Kulturen umzugehen.\nB: Das steht in jeder Stellenanzeige.",exampleSrc:"A: Intercultural competence is in demand.\nB: What does that mean?\nA: The ability to deal with different cultures.\nB: It is in every job ad.",funFact:"'Interkulturelle Kompetenz' and 'Sprachkompetenz' appear on nearly every German job ad. The Latin root 'competentia' meant meeting together, a nice image for skills that bring people together."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Stereotyp",src:"a stereotype (noun)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Greek 'stereos' + 'typos.' Neuter.\n'Stereotype abbauen' (to dismantle stereotypes).",example:"A: Stereotype sind vereinfachte Bilder.\nB: Jeder hat welche.\nA: Kann man Stereotype abbauen?\nB: Durch Begegnung und Reflexion.",exampleSrc:"A: Stereotypes are simplified images.\nB: Everyone has them.\nA: Can you break down stereotypes?\nB: Through encounter and reflection.",funFact:"As a neuter noun, das Stereotyp means the fixed image itself. 'Stereotype abbauen' (to break down stereotypes) is a common goal in German public discourse. Greek roots: stereos (solid) + typos (impression)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"jemand",src:"someone, somebody",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Je (ever) + man (one) + d. Can be declined:\njemandes, jemandem, jemanden. Often undeclined.",example:"A: Jemand hat angerufen.\nB: Wer?\nA: Ich weiß nicht. Jemand von der Uni.\nB: Hat jemand eine Nachricht hinterlassen?",exampleSrc:"A: Someone called.\nB: Who?\nA: I don't know. Someone from the university.\nB: Did someone leave a message?",funFact:"Je (ever) + man (one) + d. Can decline: jemandes, jemandem, jemanden. But in speech, often left undeclined. The positive counterpart to niemand."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Individualismus",src:"individualism"},{trg:"die Kompetenz",src:"competence, skill"},{trg:"das Stereotyp",src:"a stereotype (noun)"},{trg:"jemand",src:"someone, somebody"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"niemand",src:"nobody, no one",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Nie (never) + mand. The negation of jemand.\nCan be declined like jemand.",example:"A: Niemand ist perfekt.\nB: Das stimmt.\nA: Niemand sollte ausgegrenzt werden.\nB: Darin sind wir uns einig.",exampleSrc:"A: Nobody is perfect.\nB: That is true.\nA: Nobody should be excluded.\nB: On that we agree.",funFact:"Nie (never) + mand. The negative of jemand. 'Niemand ist perfekt' (Nobody is perfect). Can decline like jemand but often left undeclined in speech."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Niemand sollte ausgegrenzt werden.' 'Niemand' ist das Gegenteil von...",opts:["jemand","irgendwer","jedweder","mancher"],ans:"jemand",hint:"Nie (never) + mand. The direct negative of the positive indefinite pronoun for 'somebody.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"irgendwer",src:"someone or other, anyone at all",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Irgend (some/any) + wer (who). More indefinite than jemand.\nThe irgend- prefix adds vagueness.",example:"A: Irgendwer muss es tun.\nB: Aber wer?\nA: Irgendwer wird sich melden.\nB: Hoffentlich bald.",exampleSrc:"A: Someone or other has to do it.\nB: But who?\nA: Someone or other will step forward.\nB: Hopefully soon.",funFact:"Irgend (some/any) + wer (who). More vague than jemand. The irgend- prefix adds indefiniteness. 'Irgendwer muss es tun' (Someone or other has to do it)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"irgendetwas",src:"something or other, anything at all",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Irgend + etwas. More indefinite than etwas alone.\nColloquially shortened to 'irgendwas.'",example:"A: Irgendetwas stimmt nicht.\nB: Was meinst du?\nA: Ich weiß nicht genau. Irgendetwas fühlt sich falsch an.\nB: Vielleicht die Stimmung.",exampleSrc:"A: Something or other is not right.\nB: What do you mean?\nA: I don't know exactly. Something feels wrong.\nB: Maybe the atmosphere.",funFact:"Irgend + etwas (something). Vaguer than etwas alone. Colloquially shortened to 'irgendwas.' 'Irgendetwas stimmt nicht' (Something or other is not right)."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} hat angerufen, aber ich weiss nicht, wer.",a:["Irgendwer"],opts:["Niemand","Irgendwer","Jemand","Jedweder"],hint:"A vague indefinite pronoun: irgend + wer. More uncertain than 'jemand.' Someone or other.",sSrc:"Someone or other called, but I don't know who."},
{type:"mc",q:"Interkulturelle {blank} ist in einer globalisierten Welt unverzichtbar.",opts:["Kompetenz","Herkunft","Ausgrenzung","Lebensweise"],ans:"Kompetenz",hint:"The ability or skill to do something well. From Latin 'competentia.' Think of professional qualifications."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l8b",title:"Die grosse Debatte (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die grosse Debatte (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"sämtliche",src:"all, every single one",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'samt' (together with). Stronger than 'alle':\nemphasizes completeness. No exceptions.",example:"A: Saemtliche Vorurteile müssen abgebaut werden.\nB: Alle?\nA: Ja, sämtliche. Ohne Ausnahme.\nB: Das ist ein hohes Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: Every single prejudice must be broken down.\nB: All of them?\nA: Yes, every single one. Without exception.\nB: That is a high goal.",funFact:"Stronger than 'alle,' the word saemtliche emphasizes absolute completeness, no exceptions. It derives from 'samt' (together with). 'Saemtliche Vorurteile abbauen' means breaking down every single one."},
{type:"teach",trg:"jeglicher",src:"every possible, any whatsoever",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Very formal. Stronger than jeder.\nLeaves zero room for exceptions. Legal and literary.",example:"A: Jegliche Diskriminierung ist verboten.\nB: Auch indirekte?\nA: Ja, jegliche Form.\nB: Das Gesetz lässt keinen Spielraum.",exampleSrc:"A: Any discrimination whatsoever is prohibited.\nB: Even indirect?\nA: Yes, every possible form.\nB: The law leaves no room.",funFact:"Very formal. Stronger than jeder. Leaves zero room for exceptions. 'Jegliche Diskriminierung ist verboten' (Any discrimination whatsoever is prohibited). Legal and literary register."},
{type:"teach",trg:"jedweder",src:"every single, any whatsoever (literary)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Jed + weder (either one). Even more formal\nthan jeglicher. Literary and legal. Rarely spoken.",example:"A: Jedwede Form von Rassismus ist inakzeptabel.\nB: Das ist eine starke Aussage.\nA: Jedweder bedeutet: ohne jede Ausnahme.\nB: Ein Wort für offizielle Texte.",exampleSrc:"A: Every single form of racism is unacceptable.\nB: That is a strong statement.\nA: Jedweder means: without any exception.\nB: A word for official texts.",funFact:"Jed + weder (either). Even more formal than jeglicher. Literary and legal register. Rarely spoken. 'Jedwede Form von Rassismus' (every single form of racism)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ein jeder",src:"each and every one",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"Ein + jeder. Elevated style. More emphatic than\nplain 'jeder.' Almost biblical in tone.",example:"A: Ein jeder trägt Verantwortung.\nB: Für was?\nA: Für die Gesellschaft.\nB: Ein jeder kann etwas beitragen.",exampleSrc:"A: Each and every one bears responsibility.\nB: For what?\nA: For society.\nB: Each and every one can contribute something.",funFact:"Ein + jeder. Elevated register. More emphatic than simple 'jeder.' Almost biblical in tone. 'Ein jeder trägt Verantwortung' (Each and every one bears responsibility)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"notwendigerweise",src:"necessarily",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Notwendig (necessary) + -erweise. An academic\nqualifier. Precision language.",example:"A: Vielfalt führt nicht notwendigerweise zu Toleranz.\nB: Warum nicht?\nA: Man muss aktiv daran arbeiten.\nB: Vielfalt allein reicht nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Diversity does not necessarily lead to tolerance.\nB: Why not?\nA: You have to actively work on it.\nB: Diversity alone is not enough.",funFact:"Notwendig (necessary) + -erweise. An academic qualifier. Precision language. 'Vielfalt führt nicht notwendigerweise zu Toleranz' (Diversity does not necessarily lead to tolerance)."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"jeglicher",src:"every possible, any whatsoever"},{trg:"jedweder",src:"every single, any whatsoever (literary)"},{trg:"ein jeder",src:"each and every one"},{trg:"notwendigerweise",src:"necessarily"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"zwangslaeufig",src:"inevitably, necessarily",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Zwang (force) + laeufig (running). Stronger than\nnotwendigerweise. Something that cannot be stopped.",example:"A: Das führt zwangslaeufig zu Konflikten.\nB: Immer?\nA: Nicht immer, aber oft.\nB: Zwangslaeufig klingt endgueltig.",exampleSrc:"A: That inevitably leads to conflicts.\nB: Always?\nA: Not always, but often.\nB: Inevitably sounds final.",funFact:"Zwang (compulsion) + laeufig (running). Running by compulsion: something that cannot be stopped. Stronger than notwendigerweise. 'Das führt zwangslaeufig zu Konflikten.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das führt zwangslaeufig zu Konflikten.' Was bedeutet 'zwangslaeufig'?",opts:["möglicherweise","selten","unvermeidlich, unausweichlich","niemals"],ans:"unvermeidlich, unausweichlich",hint:"Zwang (compulsion) + laeufig (running). Running by force of necessity. Something that cannot be stopped."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zurechtkommen",src:"to cope, to manage",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Zurecht (right) + kommen (to come). Separable:\n'Ich komme damit zurecht.' To cope or manage.",example:"A: Kommst du mit der Situation zurecht?\nB: Es ist nicht einfach.\nA: Man muss damit zurechtkommen.\nB: Ja, Schritt für Schritt.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you coping with the situation?\nB: It is not easy.\nA: One has to manage.\nB: Yes, step by step.",funFact:"Zurecht (rightly/properly) + kommen (to come). Separable: 'Ich komme damit zurecht.' Finding your way properly. 'Mit der neuen Situation zurechtkommen' (to cope with the new situation)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wertschätzen",src:"to appreciate, to value",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Wert (value) + schätzen (to appreciate). More active\nthan respecting: one actively values and honors.",example:"A: Wir sollten Vielfalt wertschätzen.\nB: Was bedeutet wertschätzen genau?\nA: Den Wert erkennen und ehren.\nB: Mehr als nur respektieren.",exampleSrc:"A: We should appreciate diversity.\nB: What does appreciate mean exactly?\nA: To recognize and honor the value.\nB: More than just respecting.",funFact:"Wert (value) + schätzen (to estimate). Estimating someone's worth highly. More active than respektieren: you actively assess and honor value. 'Vielfalt wertschätzen' (to appreciate diversity)."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Wer andere wertschätzt, der gewinnt Respekt. Derjenige, der diskriminiert, verliert ihn.' Beide Saetze kombinieren...",opts:["nur Verweiswörter ohne einen zugehörigen Relativsatz","nur Kausalsaetze ohne Pronomen","nur Fugenelemente","verallgemeinernde Relativsaetze mit Verweiswörtern"],ans:"verallgemeinernde Relativsaetze mit Verweiswörtern",hint:"'Wer...der' is a generalizing relative clause. 'Derjenige, der...' is a demonstrative with relative clause."},
{type:"fb",s:"Toleranz und Respekt: {1} ist passiv, letzterer aktiv.",a:["Erstere"],opts:["Erstere","Letztere","Dieselbe","Diejenige"],hint:"The first of the two terms mentioned. 'Toleranz' was named first.",sSrc:"Tolerance and respect: the former is passive, the latter active."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Kompositum verwendet das korrekte Fugenelement?",opts:["Identitaetkrise (kein Fugenelement im Wort)","Identitaetskrise (Fugen-s nach -taet)","Identitaetenkrise (Fugen-en)","Identitaeterkrise (Fugen-er)"],ans:"Identitaetskrise (Fugen-s nach -taet)",hint:"The base noun belongs to a suffix group that consistently takes one specific linking element. Check the verb_table for which suffixes always use the same connector."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1}, was die Gesellschaft braucht, ist nicht {2} Meinung, sondern Vielfalt der Meinung{3}freiheit.",blanks:{"1":"Das","2":"dieselbe","3":"s"},pool:["Das","dieselbe","s","Alles","die gleiche","n"],hint:"Three constructs: a generalizing relative clause opener (das/alles + was), a demonstrative for sameness (ending in -selbe), and the correct Fugenelement for 'Meinung'. Three different grammatical layers in one sentence.",sSrc:"That which society needs is not the same opinion, but diversity of freedom of opinion."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Jegliche Diskriminierung ist verboten. Jedwede Form von Ausgrenzung auch.' Wie unterscheiden sich jegliche und jedwede von jede?",opts:["Sie bedeuten tatsächlich etwas anderes und sind daher nicht austauschbar","Sie sind eher umgangssprachlich","Sie sind emphatischer und formeller, schliessen jede Ausnahme aus","Es gibt keinen Unterschied im Gebrauch"],ans:"Sie sind emphatischer und formeller, schliessen jede Ausnahme aus",hint:"Both are stronger than the standard universal quantifier. They leave zero room for exceptions. Legal and literary register."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Fugenelement nach schwachen Substantiven wie 'Minderheit': Minderheit + {1} + ...",a:["en"],opts:["s","n","en"],hint:"Feminine nouns ending in -heit follow a different pattern than -ung nouns. Look at compounds like Menschenwürde or Staatenbund for the pattern.",sSrc:"The Fugenelement after nouns like Minderheit is: en"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"jemand",src:"someone"},{trg:"niemand",src:"nobody"},{trg:"sämtliche",src:"all/every single"},{trg:"jedweder",src:"every whatsoever"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'jeglicher'?",opts:["descent, lineage","every possible, any whatsoever","every single, any whatsoever (literary)","someone, somebody"],ans:"every possible, any whatsoever",hint:"An emphatic form of 'jeder'. Covers absolutely each and any instance without exception."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} trägt Verantwortung.",a:["ein jeder"],opts:["notwendigerweise","jeglicher","jedweder","ein jeder"],hint:"A literary/emphatic way of saying 'everyone'. Each and every single person.",sSrc:"Each and every one bears responsibility."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'notwendigerweise'?",opts:["necessarily","every single, any whatsoever (literary)","individualism","something or other, anything at all"],ans:"necessarily",hint:"notwendig (necessary) + -erweise (in the manner of). By logical or practical necessity."},
{type:"fb",s:"Man muss damit {1}.",a:["zurechtkommen"],opts:["jeglicher","niemand","zurechtkommen","die Abstammung"],hint:"zurecht (rightly/properly) + kommen (to come). To manage or cope with a situation.",sSrc:"One has to manage."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'wertschätzen'?",opts:["something or other, anything at all","a stereotype (noun)","to appreciate, to value","descent, lineage"],ans:"to appreciate, to value",hint:"Two parts: a noun meaning worth + a verb meaning to estimate. To hold someone in high regard."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l9",title:"Zwischen den Welten",icon:"\uD83C\uDF0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zwischen den Welten",desc:"Synthesis of Unit 32. Deploy all discourse tools: generalized relative clauses, reference words, Fugenelemente. Formulate your own worldview.",goals:["Synthesize all content from Unit 32","Use all discourse tools together","Formulate your own worldview"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erkenntnis",src:"insight, realization",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Er- + Kenntnis (knowledge). Knowledge gained through\nreason. Kant's central concept.",example:"A: Das war eine wichtige Erkenntnis.\nB: Welche?\nA: Dass Identitaet eine Bewegung ist.\nB: Zu einer Erkenntnis kommen braucht Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: That was an important insight.\nB: Which one?\nA: That identity is a movement.\nB: Arriving at an insight takes time.",funFact:"Er- + Kenntnis (knowledge). Knowledge gained through reason. Kant's central concept. 'Zu einer Erkenntnis kommen' (to arrive at an insight). The philosophical word for real understanding."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Begriff",src:"concept, term",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'begreifen' (to grasp/understand). Something\none has grasped with the mind.",example:"A: Was ist der Begriff für dieses Konzept?\nB: Identitaet.\nA: Den Begriff definieren ist schwer.\nB: Ja, manche Begriffe entziehen sich.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the term for this concept?\nB: Identity.\nA: Defining the term is difficult.\nB: Yes, some concepts elude definition.",funFact:"Literally something you have grasped with your mind. The root verb 'begreifen' means to grasp both physically and intellectually. English 'concept' works the same way, from Latin 'concipere' (to seize)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"assimilieren",src:"to assimilate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'assimilare.' Reflexive: 'sich assimilieren.'\nAssimilation erases differences.",example:"A: Muss man sich assimilieren?\nB: Das ist umstritten.\nA: Assimilieren bedeutet, Unterschiede aufzugeben.\nB: Integration bewahrt sie.",exampleSrc:"A: Must one assimilate?\nB: That is disputed.\nA: To assimilate means to give up differences.\nB: Integration preserves them.",funFact:"The German debate is clear: Integration preserves your identity, while assimilieren dissolves it. Reflexive as 'sich assimilieren,' it means giving up what makes you different. Latin root: 'assimilare' (to make alike)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie {1} man Identitaet? Jeder hat eine andere Antwort.",a:["definiert"],opts:["definiert","assimiliert","ableitet","einordnet"],hint:"From Latin 'definire' (to set boundaries). Drawing boundaries around a concept. Non-separable -ieren verb.",sSrc:"How does one define identity? Everyone has a different answer."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ableiten",src:"to derive, to deduce",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ab (from) + leiten (to lead). Separable:\n'Ich leite daraus ab.' Academic vocabulary.",example:"A: Was kann man daraus ableiten?\nB: Dass Toleranz aktiv sein muss.\nA: Ich leite eine andere Erkenntnis ab.\nB: Welche?",exampleSrc:"A: What can one derive from that?\nB: That tolerance must be active.\nA: I derive a different insight.\nB: Which one?",funFact:"Ab (from) + leiten (to lead). Separable: 'Ich leite daraus ab.' Leading a conclusion away from evidence. Academic reasoning vocabulary."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beeinflussen",src:"to influence",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + Einfluss (influence). Inseparable.\nThe be- prefix turns Einfluss into a verb.",example:"A: Die Herkunft beeinflusst die Identitaet.\nB: Wie stark?\nA: Stark, aber nicht vollständig.\nB: Man kann sich auch davon loesen.",exampleSrc:"A: Heritage influences identity.\nB: How strongly?\nA: Strongly, but not completely.\nB: One can also break free from it.",funFact:"Be- + Einfluss (influence). Not separable. The be- prefix makes Einfluss (noun) into a verb. Making the influence flow into something. 'Die Herkunft beeinflusst die Identitaet.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"definieren",src:"to define",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'definire' (to set limits).\nInseparable. To draw boundaries around a concept.",example:"A: Wie definiert man Identitaet?\nB: Das ist schwer.\nA: Jeder definiert sie anders.\nB: Genau das macht den Begriff so komplex.",exampleSrc:"A: How does one define identity?\nB: That is difficult.\nA: Everyone defines it differently.\nB: That is exactly what makes the concept so complex.",funFact:"The Latin root 'definire' literally meant to set boundaries. Defining something means drawing lines around a concept. Definieren looks and sounds nearly identical across all European languages."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Herkunft beeinflusst die Identitaet. 'Beeinflussen' ist...",opts:["trennbar, mit aus- Praefix","nicht trennbar, mit be- Praefix","reflexiv, mit sich","ein -ieren Verb"],ans:"nicht trennbar, mit be- Praefix",hint:"Be- makes Einfluss (noun) into a verb. The be- prefix creates inseparable verbs in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einordnen",src:"to classify, to categorize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein (in) + ordnen (to order). Separable: 'Ich ordne das ein.'\nCan be negative: people resist being categorized.",example:"A: Man sollte Menschen nicht vorschnell einordnen.\nB: Warum nicht?\nA: Weil Kategorien vereinfachen.\nB: Jeder Mensch ist komplexer als jede Kategorie.",exampleSrc:"A: One should not hastily classify people.\nB: Why not?\nA: Because categories simplify.\nB: Every person is more complex than any category.",funFact:"Ein (in) + ordnen (to order). Separable: 'Ich ordne das ein.' Placing something into an order. Can be negative: people resist being eingeordnet (classified)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gleichstellen",src:"to put on equal footing",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Gleich (equal) + stellen (to place). Separable.\nThe legal version of equality.",example:"A: Alle Menschen sollten gleichgestellt werden.\nB: Im Gesetz sind sie es.\nA: Man stellt sie formal gleich.\nB: Aber die Realitaet hinkt hinterher.",exampleSrc:"A: All people should be put on equal footing.\nB: In the law they are.\nA: They are formally made equal.\nB: But reality lags behind.",funFact:"Gleich (equal) + stellen (to place). Separable: 'Man stellt sie gleich.' The legal version of equality: placing two things at the same level."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sensibilisieren",src:"to sensitize, to raise awareness",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Sensibel + -isieren. To make someone more aware\nof a topic. Education and policy vocabulary.",example:"A: Wir müssen für Diskriminierung sensibilisieren.\nB: Wie?\nA: Durch Workshops und Bildung.\nB: Sensibilisierung ist der erste Schritt.",exampleSrc:"A: We must raise awareness of discrimination.\nB: How?\nA: Through workshops and education.\nB: Sensitization is the first step.",funFact:"Sensibel (sensitive) + -isieren. Making someone more sensitive to an issue. Educational and political vocabulary. 'Für Diskriminierung sensibilisieren' (to raise awareness of discrimination)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir müssen die Gesellschaft für Diskriminierung {1}.",a:["sensibilisieren"],opts:["definieren","einordnen","sensibilisieren","gleichstellen"],hint:"Making people more aware and sensitive to an issue. From 'sensibel' + -isieren. An education verb.",sSrc:"We must raise awareness of discrimination in society."}
]},
{id:"deu_r32l9b",title:"Zwischen den Welten (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zwischen den Welten (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"umdenken",src:"to rethink, to change one's thinking",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Um (around) + denken (to think). Separable: 'Wir denken um.'\nA paradigm shift in one word.",example:"A: Die Gesellschaft muss umdenken.\nB: In welcher Hinsicht?\nA: Beim Thema Identitaet.\nB: Umdenken braucht Zeit und Mut.",exampleSrc:"A: Society must rethink.\nB: In what regard?\nA: On the topic of identity.\nB: Rethinking takes time and courage.",funFact:"Um (re-/around) + denken (to think). Separable: 'Wir denken um.' Turning your thinking around. A paradigm shift in one word. 'Die Gesellschaft muss umdenken.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"zukunftsorientiert",src:"future-oriented",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Zukunft + s (linking -s) + orientiert. Three-part\ncompound with linking -s. Looking forward.",example:"A: Eine zukunftsorientierte Gesellschaft investiert in Bildung.\nB: Und in Technologie.\nA: Zukunftsorientiert denken ist wichtig.\nB: Die Zukunft beginnt heute.",exampleSrc:"A: A future-oriented society invests in education.\nB: And in technology.\nA: Thinking in a future-oriented way is important.\nB: The future begins today.",funFact:"Zukunft (future) + s (Fugen-s) + orientiert (oriented). Three-part compound with Fugen-s. Looking forward rather than backward. 'Eine zukunftsorientierte Gesellschaft.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"identifizieren",src:"to identify (pinpoint)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'identificare.' Inseparable.\nWithout 'sich': to recognize. With 'sich': to identify with.",example:"A: Probleme identifizieren ist der erste Schritt.\nB: Und dann?\nA: Lösungen finden.\nB: Man muss genau identifizieren, was das Problem ist.",exampleSrc:"A: Identifying problems is the first step.\nB: And then?\nA: Finding solutions.\nB: One must precisely identify what the problem is.",funFact:"Without 'sich,' identifizieren means to pinpoint or recognize: 'Probleme identifizieren.' With 'sich,' it means to identify with something personally. Two very different meanings from one Latin root ('identificare')."},
{type:"teach",trg:"man",src:"one, you (impersonal), people",pos:"pron",gender:null,note:"[V1 review at advanced level.] The impersonal\npronoun. Not gross (not man). More common than in English.",example:"A: Man sagt, dass Berlin weltoffen ist.\nB: Stimmt das?\nA: Man erlebt es täglich.\nB: Man gewöhnt sich daran.",exampleSrc:"A: People say that Berlin is cosmopolitan.\nB: Is that true?\nA: One experiences it daily.\nB: One gets used to it.",funFact:"The impersonal pronoun. Not capitalized (unlike Mann = man). 'Man' is used far more in German than 'one' in English. 'Man sagt' (people say) is everywhere."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mancher",src:"some, many a",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[V1 review.] Declined like dieser.\n'Manche' (plural) = some. Less definite than 'viele.'",example:"A: Mancher Mensch sucht ein Leben lang nach Identitaet.\nB: Manche finden sie nie.\nA: Manche früh, manche spät.\nB: Das ist menschlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Many a person searches a lifetime for identity.\nB: Some never find it.\nA: Some early, some late.\nB: That is human.",funFact:"Some, many a. Declines like dieser. 'Manche' (plural) = some. A less definite quantifier than 'einige' or 'viele.' 'Mancher Mensch' (many a person)."},
{type:"tip",title:"Identitaet auf Deutsch: eine philosophische Tradition",text:"German has unique words for identity concepts that other languages can barely translate.\n\nWeltanschauung: your comprehensive view of the world.\nBildung: not just education, but self-formation.\nHeimat: the place where you belong (not just birthplace).\nZugehörigkeit: the feeling of being part of something.\nSehnsucht: deep longing for something unreachable.\n\nThese words shape how Germans think about identity. Language does not just describe the concepts. It creates them.\nWhoever speaks German thinks differently about identity.",deepDive:{title:"German identity vocabulary in philosophy",text:"Germany produced some of the world's most influential identity philosophers. Kant explored Erkenntnis (knowledge through reason). Hegel wrote about Bewusstsein (consciousness) and its development. Marx examined Entfremdung (alienation). Heidegger questioned Dasein (being-there). Arendt analyzed Zugehörigkeit (belonging) in political life.\n\nThese thinkers did not just use German words. They created concepts that could only exist in German. Weltanschauung, Bildung, Heimat, Sehnsucht: these are untranslatable because they carry centuries of philosophical weight. Learning German means learning to think in these categories."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Wer umdenkt, der verändert die Gesellschaftsstruktur. Dieselbe Erkenntnis hatten schon die Aufklaerer.' Welche Konstrukte erscheinen?",opts:["nur einfache Relativsaetze ohne Verweiswort","nur Fugenelemente in Komposita","nur Verweiswörter ohne Relativsatz","Relativsatz + Fugenelement + Verweiswort"],ans:"Relativsatz + Fugenelement + Verweiswort",hint:"Count the distinct constructs: a free relative clause opener, a linking element inside a compound noun, and a demonstrative pronoun referring back. All three are present in this single sentence."},
{type:"fb",s:"Alles, {1} ich in Deutschland erlebt habe, hat mich geformt.",a:["was"],opts:["was","das","wer","welches"],hint:"After indefinite pronouns like 'alles' or 'nichts', the relative pronoun is not the usual definite article form. It is a special relative word.",sSrc:"Everything that I have experienced in Germany has shaped me."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Fugenelement ist korrekt? Freiheit_kampf",opts:["Freiheitkampf (kein Verbindungselement)","Freiheitskampf (Fugen-s)","Freiheitenkampf (Fugen-en)","Freiheiterkampf (Fugen-er)"],ans:"Freiheitskampf (Fugen-s)",hint:"Nouns ending in -heit, -keit, and -schaft all follow the same rule. Look at the suffix family pattern in the verb_table."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} andere respektiert, {2} wird selbst respektiert. {3} Erkenntnis ist zeitlos.",blanks:{"1":"Wer","2":"der","3":"Diese"},pool:["Wer","der","Diese","Was","den","Dieselbe"],hint:"Generalizing relative clause (wer...der) + demonstrative (diese). 'Wer andere respektiert, der wird selbst respektiert.'",sSrc:"Whoever respects others is respected. This insight is timeless."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Erkenntnis",src:"insight/realization"},{trg:"Weltanschauung",src:"worldview"},{trg:"Zusammenleben",src:"coexistence"},{trg:"Menschenwürde",src:"human dignity"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'sich assimilieren' im Vergleich zu 'sich integrieren'?",opts:["Beide sind bedeutungsgleich: man wird Teil einer Gesellschaft","Assimilation bewahrt die eigene Identit\u00e4t, Integration l\u00f6scht sie","Assimilation l\u00f6scht Unterschiede, Integration bewahrt sie","Integration ist st\u00e4rker als Assimilation"],ans:"Assimilation l\u00f6scht Unterschiede, Integration bewahrt sie",hint:"Think about what happens to your original identity in each process. One preserves differences, the other dissolves them."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'umdenken'?",opts:["to rethink, to change one's thinking","one, you (impersonal), people","to assimilate","to classify, to categorize"],ans:"to rethink, to change one's thinking",hint:"um- (around/re-) + denken (to think). To think in an entirely new direction, to shift perspective."},
{type:"fb",s:"Eine {1}e Gesellschaft investiert in Bildung.",a:["zukunftsorientiert"],opts:["einordnen","gleichstellen","zukunftsorientiert","identifizieren"],hint:"Zukunft (future) + orientiert (oriented). Focused on what lies ahead.",sSrc:"A future-oriented society invests in education."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'identifizieren'?",opts:["to sensitize, to raise awareness","to classify, to categorize","to identify (pinpoint)","to define"],ans:"to identify (pinpoint)",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. To determine exactly what or who something is."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} sagt, dass Berlin weltoffen ist.",a:["man"],opts:["der Begriff","umdenken","die Erkenntnis","man"],hint:"The impersonal pronoun for 'people in general'. NOT the English word for an adult male.",sSrc:"People say that Berlin is cosmopolitan."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'mancher'?",opts:["some, many a","concept, term","to assimilate","to classify, to categorize"],ans:"some, many a",hint:"An indefinite pronoun. Implies a surprising quantity of people or items, not just a few."}
]}
]};

export default UNIT_32;
